<DOCNO> APW19990612.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Boxer-Lawsuit Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Associated Press, in a story about  
Time Inc. being ordered to pay ex-heavyweight boxer Randall ``Tex'' 
Cobb $10.7 million for a 1993 Sports Illustrated article, 
erroneously reported Friday that Sports Illustrated had said Cobb 
tested positive for cocaine. Sports Illustrated did not say Cobb 
tested positive for cocaine. It said Cobb had flunked a post-fight 
drug test. In a follow-up, Sports Illustrated said that Cobb had 
tested positive for marijuana. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 20:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest in Orange County Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Calif. (AP) -- A sheriff's deputy was shot  
repeatedly with an assault rifle outside a convenience store early 
Saturday, and authorities arrested a man for the crime a few hours 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Brad Riches' patrol car was riddled with bullets from an  
AK-47 in the predawn attack, said Lt. Steve Fauchier. 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice Gerald Steskal, 39, was arrested and booked for  
investigation of murder. He was held without bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Steskal was toting the assault rifle under his arm when he  
bought a pack of cigarettes at a convenience store before walking 
out and allegedly shooting Riches about 1 a.m., Fauchier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riches, 34, had pulled into the store's parking lot and noticed  
an armed man but was unable to draw his weapon, though he was able 
to send a radio code that an emergency broadcast was about to 
follow, Orange County Sheriff Mike Carona said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a homicide that is as brutal as you can possibly  
imagine,'' Carona said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steskal had previous arrests for drunken driving, drug  
possession and assaulting an officer, but authorities were unable 
to say whether he was convicted of any crimes, Fauchier said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks Coach Reaps Millions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy made millions when the New York  
Knicks made it to the NBA Finals on Friday night with a 90-82 
victory over the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	An option year in Van Gundy's contract worth $3.5 million became  
guaranteed when he led his team out of the Eastern Conference 
finals. He also will reportedly receive a $500,000 bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really care what's in there, I just want to win,'' Van  
Gundy said Friday after the Knicks held their shootaround in 
preparation for Game 6 against the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy's potential windfall headlined the front page of one  
of the city's tabloids Friday along with a rare photo of Van Gundy 
smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	The dour-faced coach, in his fourth season running the team, is  
currently making $2 million per season -- the same amount Doc Rivers 
will be getting from Orlando next season despite never having 
coached at any level. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he wasn't exactly sure what's in his contract  
because he keeps it in a safety deposit box. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing about this job is, I'm fine (financially).  
Wanting to win has zero to do with money,'' Van Gundy said. ``You 
can't buy your way into something that's worthwhile, and the only 
thing worthwhile out of here is trying to be the best team for one 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his team's postseason success, Van Gundy has not  
received a vote of confidence from Madison Square Garden 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	Garden president Dave Checketts, who demoted general manager  
Ernie Grunfeld in April because of a rift between the GM and coach, 
has steadfastly insisted that all team personnel, including the 
coach, will have their performances reviewed at the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts met with former Chicago Bulls coach Phil Jackson in  
April when the Knicks were 21-21 and in jeopardy of missing the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts subsequently lied to Van Gundy by denying such a  
meeting ever took place, then met with the coach during the 
second-round series against Atlanta and apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about whether Van Gundy would even want to return to  
the Knicks has been rampant ever since. For the past two weeks, Van 
Gundy has brushed aside all queries about his job status. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy became a risk-taker in the Eastern Conference finals.  
He tinkered with his starting lineup before Game 4 by inserting 
Latrell Sprewell and removing Kurt Thomas. And in Game 5, he 
curiously kept Marcus Camby on the bench for the first 10 minutes 
of the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``By starting Latrell, it was neither genius ... nor stupidity  
in Game 4,'' Van Gundy said. ``It was what I felt was in the best 
interest of the team. That's how I make every decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy took a lot of criticism when the Sprewell move seemed  
to backfire in Game 4. But those same critics were lauding the move 
after Game 5 when Sprewell unleashed an array of offensive moves 
and had his best game of the series with 29 points. 
</P>
<P>
	With Camby, the coach decided to keep him out for the bulk of  
the third quarter because he had three fouls. He wanted Camby 
available for the entire fourth quarter, and he didn't want him 
playing tentatively because of foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The move paid off.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just really thankful that I'm a part of a team that's  
still playing,'' Van Gundy said. ``And what small part I play in 
it, I take very seriously. I do the job the best I can. '' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, it meant departing from what got the Knicks here  
and taking a gamble or two to try to help offset the loss of center 
Patrick Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you become paralyzed by the thought that you may be  
criticized for doing something, you're never going to be the risk 
taker you need to be as a good coach. Risk taking is part of it. If 
it doesn't work out, you've got to accept the responsibility for it 
not working out,'' Van Gundy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks Coach Reaps Millions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy made millions when the New York  
Knicks made it to the NBA Finals on Friday night with a 90-82 
victory over the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	An option year in Van Gundy's contract worth $3.5 million became  
guaranteed when he led his team out of the Eastern Conference 
finals. He also will reportedly receive a $500,000 bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really care what's in there, I just want to win,'' Van  
Gundy said Friday after the Knicks held their shootaround in 
preparation for Game 6 against the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy's potential windfall headlined the front page of one  
of the city's tabloids Friday along with a rare photo of Van Gundy 
smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	The dour-faced coach, in his fourth season running the team, is  
currently making $2 million per season -- the same amount Doc Rivers 
will be getting from Orlando next season despite never having 
coached at any level. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he wasn't exactly sure what's in his contract  
because he keeps it in a safety deposit box. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing about this job is, I'm fine (financially).  
Wanting to win has zero to do with money,'' Van Gundy said. ``You 
can't buy your way into something that's worthwhile, and the only 
thing worthwhile out of here is trying to be the best team for one 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his team's postseason success, Van Gundy has not  
received a vote of confidence from Madison Square Garden 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	Garden president Dave Checketts, who demoted general manager  
Ernie Grunfeld in April because of a rift between the GM and coach, 
has steadfastly insisted that all team personnel, including the 
coach, will have their performances reviewed at the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts met with former Chicago Bulls coach Phil Jackson in  
April when the Knicks were 21-21 and in jeopardy of missing the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts subsequently lied to Van Gundy by denying such a  
meeting ever took place, then met with the coach during the 
second-round series against Atlanta and apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about whether Van Gundy would even want to return to  
the Knicks has been rampant ever since. For the past two weeks, Van 
Gundy has brushed aside all queries about his job status. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy became a risk-taker in the Eastern Conference finals.  
He tinkered with his starting lineup before Game 4 by inserting 
Latrell Sprewell and removing Kurt Thomas. And in Game 5, he 
curiously kept Marcus Camby on the bench for the first 10 minutes 
of the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``By starting Latrell, it was neither genius ... nor stupidity  
in Game 4,'' Van Gundy said. ``It was what I felt was in the best 
interest of the team. That's how I make every decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy took a lot of criticism when the Sprewell move seemed  
to backfire in Game 4. But those same critics were lauding the move 
after Game 5 when Sprewell unleashed an array of offensive moves 
and had his best game of the series with 29 points. 
</P>
<P>
	With Camby, the coach decided to keep him out for the bulk of  
the third quarter because he had three fouls. He wanted Camby 
available for the entire fourth quarter, and he didn't want him 
playing tentatively because of foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The move paid off.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just really thankful that I'm a part of a team that's  
still playing,'' Van Gundy said. ``And what small part I play in 
it, I take very seriously. I do the job the best I can. '' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, it meant departing from what got the Knicks here  
and taking a gamble or two to try to help offset the loss of center 
Patrick Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you become paralyzed by the thought that you may be  
criticized for doing something, you're never going to be the risk 
taker you need to be as a good coach. Risk taking is part of it. If 
it doesn't work out, you've got to accept the responsibility for it 
not working out,'' Van Gundy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
