<DOCNO> APW19990612.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 12:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Valentine Has Weird Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As Bobby Valentine sat behind his desk Saturday  
morning, the New York Mets manager was asked if he was a lightning 
rod for turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole life. This week was nothing new,'' he said. ``It's  
just a little more fun when I get down for people to kick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a 10-day period, there was an eight-game losing streak  
followed by a four-game winning streak. He found out two of his 
outfielders were put on waivers. Then he was told general manager 
Steve Phillips was firing three of his coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	There was an argument with a reporter and a screaming match with  
Bobby Bonilla, who refused to pinch hit Tuesday night. To top it 
off, Valentine was caught in the Mets' dugout wearing a disguise 
Wednesday night after umpires had ejected him. 
</P>
<P>
	In retrospect, he said he never should have donned the fake  
mustache and sunglasses and returned to the dugout, earning a 
two-game suspension from the National League. 
</P>
<P>
	But everything he does garners attention.  
</P>
<P>
	Major league managers are in the spotlight, and it's rarely more  
glaring than in New York, where the slightest misstep turns them 
into tennis balls for the tabloids. 
</P>
<P>
	Particularly Valentine.  
</P>
<P>
	Sparky Anderson once called him ``wonderfully arrogant.''  
</P>
<P>
	``When I was playing against him, you had a sense of the  
confident, cocky air he had about him,'' former Texas GM Tom Grieve 
said while Valentine was his manager. ``But when you get to know 
him, you find out what a big heart he's got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine can be brusque. He can be outspoken at times. And he  
certainly isn't shy about taking credit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think things are as fragile as people would like it to  
be,'' he said Saturday. ``It's a strong foundation, and it's built 
on those players in the clubhouse. We might have had a couple of 
windows broken, but the structure's still there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't just talking about events of the past week.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm referring to the abyss that was here 2 1/2 years ago,'' he  
said, thinking back to when he replaced Dallas Green on Aug. 26, 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine, 49, has spent his entire life in baseball -- he even  
married the daughter of Ralph Branca, who gave up the home run to 
Bobby Thomson that gave the New York Giants the 1951 NL pennant 
over the Brooklyn Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	After playing in the majors from 1969-79 -- he was .260 career  
hitter -- Valentine managed the Texas Rangers from May 1985 until 
July 1992, setting a major league record for most games managing 
one team without finishing first (1,186). 
</P>
<P>
	He managed in Japan, then returned to the Mets' Norfolk farm  
club in 1996 and took over the major league team after it went 
59-72 under Green. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets have been completely transformed, but have fallen short  
of the playoffs, finishing 88-74 in each of his two full seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	When Phillips fired the coaches last Saturday night, the Mets  
were 27-28, dropping under .500 for the first time since they lost 
the season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	New York responded with a four-game winning streak. Even when  
the Mets were losing, Valentine said the team was playing well. On 
Saturday, he termed it ``10 days of outstanding baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The clubhouse, he said, was now ``placid and peaceful,'' a sign  
that he and Bonilla may have reached a truce. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took a terribly disruptive situation and calmed it,  
straightened it and made it whole,'' Valentine said. ``Today, as 
opposed to a couple of days ago, things are a lot calmer.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
