<DOCNO> APW19990612.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 13:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at Knicks' Improbable Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Forget the fact that nobody thought it was  
possible for the Knicks to make it to the finals. Not too long ago, 
nobody in New York even thought they were any good. 
</P>
<P>
	There was good reason for all the naysayers to be ganging up on  
the Knicks just a few weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The franchise center kept missing the final shot, the coach was  
too stubborn to give adequate playing time to the newest members of 
the team, the general manager was too insecure about his own risky 
moves to let the coach do what he thought was best for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	In short, the Knicks were a basket case and New York hated them.  
</P>
<P>
	Boos and insults rained down from the fans. The sports talks  
shows were filled with statements like: ``Trade Sprewell.'' ``Trade 
Houston.'' ``Cut Ewing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one believed in the Knicks.  
</P>
<P>
	Well, almost no one.  
</P>
<P>
	``You guys buried us, covered us, started shoveling dirt on  
us,'' Patrick Ewing said. ``We still believed in ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A look at some of the key moments in this season of turmoil that  
has somehow continued into mid-June with the Knicks having a shot 
at the franchise's first title since 1973: 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 23 -- Latrell Sprewell sits on a podium alongside coach Jeff  
Van Gundy after the Knicks acquire him in a trade with Golden 
State. ``I'm out to start all over and show people the real me,'' 
Sprewell said. ``I'm not the person I've been portrayed to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 25 -- Van Gundy reports that Marcus Camby, who had been  
acquired for the popular Charles Oakley, has started training camp 
out of shape. It would be one of many instances when Van Gundy 
publicly knocked Camby. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan. 27 -- Sprewell scores 27 points in his first exhibition  
game, including 21 in a 12-minute burst. The crowd loves him. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 7 -- Knicks drop to 0-2 with a home loss to Miami. Sprewell  
injures his foot, keeping him out of the next 13 games. Camby asks 
out after five minutes, telling Van Gundy he is winded. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 25 -- Knicks beat Minnesota 115-113 in overtime, improving  
to 8-3. They look like a well-oiled machine without Sprewell's 
freelancing. 
</P>
<P>
	March 9 -- Ewing limps off in the first minute with Achilles'  
tendinitis. Knicks lose to Milwaukee at the buzzer when Sprewell 
leaves Dell Curry wide open for a game-winning 3-pointer. Van 
Gundy's favorite reporters start calling Sprewell a ``chucker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	March 11 -- Knicks make last-minute effort to acquire Stephon  
Marbury from Minnesota, offering Sprewell and Chris Childs. The New 
Jersey Nets get him instead. 
</P>
<P>
	March 12 -- Knicks score just 63 points and lose by 13 to the  
miserable Chicago Bulls. On the plane ride home, little-used 
reserve Dennis Scott is goofing off with his buddies, Sprewell and 
Rick Brunson. Van Gundy cuts him. 
</P>
<P>
	March 14 -- NBC reports that Van Gundy could be fired if the  
Knicks lose their game that night against Charlotte. Van Gundy's 
wife, Kim, stands in the back of the room at his pre-game meeting 
with reporters looking concerned. Knicks win. 
</P>
<P>
	March 22 -- Fans unleash a torrent of boos as the Knicks are  
being clobbered by the Atlanta Hawks to drop to 15-12. 
</P>
<P>
	April 7 -- Knicks lose by 24 at Charlotte, dropping to 18-17. GM  
Ernie Grunfeld reportedly recommends firing Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	April 20 -- The day after a loss at Philadelphia drops the Knicks  
to 21-21, Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts sets up a 
secret meeting with former Bulls coach Phil Jackson to gauge his 
interest in coaching the team. 
</P>
<P>
	April 21 -- Grunfeld is demoted as Checketts sides with Van Gundy  
in an internal rift; Sprewell is fined $25,000 after his agent says 
he'll demand a trade if the Knicks plan to bring his client off the 
bench next season. 
</P>
<P>
	April 25 -- Playing without Ewing, the Knicks come back from a  
20-point deficit in the second half at Miami to defeat the Heat. 
They later called it the turning point of their season. 
</P>
<P>
	May 3 -- Knicks blow three huge leads before defeating Boston to  
clinch a playoff spot. 
</P>
<P>
	May 5 -- Knicks defeat Miami and Philadelphia defeats Detroit,  
locking New York into the eighth seed and a first-round matchup 
with the Heat. 
</P>
<P>
	May 16 -- Allan Houston's last second jumper takes a fortuitous  
bounce and falls through, giving the Knicks a 78-77 victory over 
the Heat in Game 5. 
</P>
<P>
	May 23 -- News breaks of the Checketts-Jackson meeting. Checketts  
denies it, then abruptly changes his story during the third quarter 
of a Game 3 victory over Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	May 24 -- Checketts meets with Van Gundy and apologizes for lying  
to him about the Jackson meeting. Checketts reiterates that Van 
Gundy's future with the team will be decided after the season. 
Knicks complete sweep of Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	June 1 -- Ewing tears his Achilles tendon during pre-game  
warmups, misses last shot as Pacers tie series 1-1. 
</P>
<P>
	June 2 -- Knicks announce that Ewing is out for the season.  
</P>
<P>
	June 6 -- Van Gundy says Sprewell will move into the starting  
lineup after begrudgingly accepting his sixth man role all season. 
</P>
<P>
	June 7 -- Knicks lose Game 4 to Indiana as the lineup switch  
backfires. 
</P>
<P>
	June 9 -- Camby is unstoppable as Knicks win Game 5 in Indiana.  
</P>
<P>
	June 11 -- Larry Johnson injured in second quarter, but Knicks  
overcome it to beat Pacers 90-82 and win Eastern Conference finals 
4-2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
