<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top NBA Prospects Show Up at Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) -- While most of the aspiring NBA draft  
picks were already in the Chicago area for the pre-draft camp, some 
of those considered the sure top choices arrived Saturday for 
physicals and to talk with the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami of Ohio forward Wally Szczerbiak expressed why most of the  
top prospects did not want to participate in the camp run by the 
NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I vaulted myself into the lottery pick area, I didn't  
want to take my chances of getting hurt,'' Szczerbiak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others virtually ensured of being among the first names called  
on June 30 in Washington, didn't sound too concerned about which 
team selected them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting picked is the only thing that matters,'' guard Jason  
Terry of Arizona said. ``Just to hear your name called is good 
enough. Once you get there, you've got to do the work, anyway, so 
you just hopefully want to get picked in a good situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland guard Steve Francis has been mentioned as being a  
possible No. 1 overall pick by the Chicago Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nice just to put on an NBA uniform of any team.''  
Francis said. ``Just to see your uniform in a store with your name 
on it is something I would want to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other top players who arrived Saturday were Duke forward Elton  
Brand, Utah guard Andre Miller and Aleksandar Radojevic, a 7-foot-3 
center from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke forward Corey Maggette, who declared for the draft after  
his freshman year, was not invited. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand, the consensus national player of the year last season as  
a sophomore, refuted assertions that he is not as tall as the 
6-foot-8 he was listed as while playing at Duke. Some have 
expressed doubts he can measure up to the competition in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad I'm here to prove the critics wrong and show my true  
height, I have the reach, I have athleticism, I have quickness, I 
have strength,'' he said. ``That's what you need in basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Szczerbiak held an open workout Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I want everyone to see what I can do, '' he said. ``I wanted  
to make sure that no one overlooks me just because they haven't 
seen me. I'm a lot more versatile and athletic than (people) 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francis, who played just one season at Maryland but may have led  
the nation in impressive highlight clips, has found himself 
compared to Allen Iverson of the Philadelphia 76ers, the NBA's 
leading scorer last season. The comparison with Iverson on and off 
the court is one Francis can live with. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I bring my own style of basketball to the NBA,''  
Francis said. ``Just because what me and Allen have been through a 
lot of people are going to try compare (us). That's a compliment to 
me because he's worked real hard to get to where he is and I've 
worked real hard to get to where I am.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
