<DOCNO> APW19990612.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 03:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abu-Jamal Protested at Commencement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- This week's commencement ceremony at  
Evergreen State College had caps, gowns and the words of condemned 
murderer Mumia Abu-Jamal echoing throughout the exercise for 13 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of the approximately 800 graduates walked out as  
Abu-Jamal's audiotaped speech was played Friday for the audience of 
several thousand. Two dozen other graduates stood and turned their 
backs, and still others wore yellow armbands of support. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters -- including Maureen Faulkner, the widow of the  
Philadelphia police officer shot by Abu-Jamal in 1981 -- also 
attended the ceremony. Abu-Jamal's participation, Ms. Faulkner 
said, was ``not fitting for a graduation ceremony. A classroom, 
maybe, but not a graduation ceremony.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another protester had a replica of an electric chair and a sign  
reading: ``A positive role model for Mumia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Students' selection of Abu-Jamal as a speaker had turned into a  
political tempest. Gov. Gary Locke canceled his scheduled 
appearance at the ceremony, and Majority Whip Tom Delay took to the 
House floor on Thursday to ask for a moment of silence to protest 
the students' choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal's jailhouse writings about the justice system and his  
efforts to win a new trial have given him worldwide attention. A 
symbol for death penalty opponents, he insists he is innocent and 
his conviction was the result a biased judge and an ineffective 
lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal has been on death row since 1982. No execution date  
has been set. He is appealing to the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Some students supported Abu-Jamal's inclusion in the ceremony.  
Malka Fenyvesi said Abu-Jamal was not invited to ``to create a lot 
of bad feelings'' but rather to create a forum for a ``marginalized 
segment of our society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks, Abu-Jamal, a former Black Panther, drew  
parallels between British colonial rule and black U.S. political 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why was it right for people to revolt against the British  
because of taxation without representation and somehow wrong for 
truly unrepresented Africans in America to revolt against 
America?'' he asked. ``For any repressed people, revolution, 
according to the Declaration of Independence, is a right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	College President Jane Jervis told the crowd before Abu-Jamal's  
remarks were played that people should ``be aware of the pain and 
outrage'' of Ms. Faulkner and police officers, and of the right of 
diverse voices to be heard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:44:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Peacekeeping Forces Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO peacekeeping forces for Kosovo and the countries that will  
provide most of the troops: 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRITAIN: 12,000 troops, including the force commander, Lt. Gen.  
Mike Jackson. He will establish a headquarters in Kosovo's capital, 
Pristina, and most of the British contingent will be deployed in 
that area. The sector includes the central Drenica region, a 
mountainous area that was a stronghold of the rebel Kosovo 
Liberation Army. Other NATO peacekeepers in this zone: Norwegians, 
who have secured the Grand Hotel and other sites in the center of 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	UNITED STATES: 7,000 troops, mostly from the Marines and the  
Army. Most will be stationed in southeastern Kosovo near the 
Macedonian border, with headquarters in Gnjilane. Although only a 
relative handful of American troops entered Kosovo on Saturday, 
U.S. Apache attack helicopters flew air cover for the mostly 
British and French convoys. The U.S. sector is in an area that was 
relatively quiet for most of the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	FRANCE: 7,000 troops. Deployed in the northern sector with  
headquarters in Kosovska Mitrovica. Will be reinforced by 1,200 
soldiers from the United Arab Emirates. The French area includes 
strategic routes from Kosovo into Serbia and Montenegro, as well as 
an area of recent fighting between Serb and KLA forces. A French 
tank regiment entered Kosovo on Saturday after being blocked for 
most of the day by a minefield that the Serbs had failed to 
identify, as provided for under the peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ITALY: 5,000 troops. Deployed in western Kosovo with  
headquarters in Pec, the scene of some of the most horrendous 
ethnic purges of the Kosovo conflict. Pec is also the seat of the 
Serbian Orthodox Church in the province and sits along a major 
route into Montenegro. The Italians are expected to begin deploying 
into Kosovo early Sunday, and their route will take them through 
scenes of recent heavy fighting between Yugoslav and ethnic 
Albanian rebel forces. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GERMANY: 8,500 troops. Stationed in the southwestern city of  
Prizren, it will be the first time the German army has been 
deployed in such large numbers since end of World War II. The 
Germans will enter Kosovo on Sunday from northern Albania, 
traveling a route where American B-52 bombers hammered Serb forces 
last weekend and where ethnic Albanian rebels tried unsuccessfully 
to open a supply corridor into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RUSSIA: Russia has said it is prepared to send up to 10,000  
troops. A convoy of Russian troops arrived in the Kosovo capital of 
Pristina early Saturday after Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov assured 
Washington they would not without a formal agreement on command and 
control relationships to NATO. The Russians effectively control 
Pristina airport, which NATO had hoped to use as a headquarters. 
NATO officials in Bosnia say another Russian force is massed near 
the Serbian border prepared to move to Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mets Honor Ted Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets honored former Red Sox great  
Ted Williams on Friday night in celebration of the 60th anniversary 
of the Hall of Famer's rookie season. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famers Tom Seaver, Yogi Berra and Ralph Kiner, as well  
as many of Williams' former teammates, were on hand for the 
ceremony before Friday night's game between the Mets and Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``You set an example for all of us who played and still set an  
example for those who play now. You are the greatest,'' Kiner said 
before presenting Williams with a silver bat. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, still recovering from a stroke, made his brief remarks  
from a golf cart on the pitcher's mound, while players from both 
teams stood attentively on the baselines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been lucky in my days in baseball,'' Williams said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was helped out of the cart by Tom Seaver and Rusty Staub  
before throwing the ceremonial first pitch to Mike Piazza. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
