<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 10:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mayors Seek Revenue From Web Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Poor Ron Kirk. The Dallas mayor and chairman  
of the U.S. Conference of Mayors city economic task force may have 
the most unenviable duty a politician can face. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk's mission is to make the public see the need for another  
tax, this one on Internet sales. In blunt terms on Saturday, Kirk 
tried to enlist his colleagues to join him in a fight for millions 
of dollars in lost tax revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have a persuasive argument before the public,'' Kirk  
said Saturday during a panel discussion at the annual mayors 
meeting. ``But we have to explain that when you are sitting at home 
in your virtual world and you have a short (circuit) and a fire 
breaks out, do you want us to send a virtual fire truck or a real 
big red fire truck'' to save you. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk and others oppose the Internet Tax Freedom Act, a law  
passed last year that places a three-year ban on taxing online 
sales and access. They said it results in fewer dollars for public 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	``People care about their schools, streets and parks but they  
don't pay for themselves,'' the mayor explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the law say they don't want to place a tax  
stranglehold on fledgling Internet trade, but the growing 
popularity of Internet shopping puts Main Street merchants -- who 
must pay a slew of local, state and federal taxes -- at a severe 
disadvantage with their electronic competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lost revenue is going to be made up by the consumer at  
some point,'' said William McCabe Jr., chairman of the 
International Council of Shopping Centers, a trade organization for 
the shopping center industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Some towns may be seeing the impact already.  
</P>
<P>
	Karen Hasara, mayor of Springfield, Ill., said her community has  
seen a recent decline in sales tax receipts from Main Street 
merchants. ``We aren't sure it's from Internet sales, but we are 
beginning to feel the effects,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the law argue that information shouldn't be taxed  
and that tax savings will stimulate further online development. 
They also maintain a single Internet transaction could become the 
target of dozens of state and local taxes without the tax 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton supported the three-year cooling off period  
before Internet taxes could be imposed, saying it would keep online 
business flourishing. 
</P>
<P>
	An independent panel appointed by Congress called the Advisory  
Commission on Electronic Commerce may ultimately decide if the 
taxman ever grabs a share of cybersales. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, which begins its work on June 22, was created to  
develop recommendations about how federal officials should handle 
taxing the multibillion dollar Internet commerce industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk, a commission member, said it shouldn't be that hard to  
figure out ways to tax online transactions with harming new online 
firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an industry that lends itself to problem solving,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Working on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid more confusion in Moscow over  
who decided to send Russian troops into Kosovo, U.S. and Russian 
negotiators worked feverishly today to design a formal job for 
Russia in the Kosovo peacekeeping force. But there was no immediate 
result and no sign the Russian column was planning to leave, as 
Russia's foreign minister had promised. Streaming into Kosovo's 
capital, almost unopposed by retreating Serbs, NATO peacekeepers 
came face-to-face today with the Russian troops who beat them to 
the city. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Suspects Some of Smallpox Weapon  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Government officials say Russia, Iraq and North  
Korea are probably concealing the deadly smallpox virus for 
military use, The New York Times reports in Sunday editions. A 
secret federal intelligence assessment was completed late last 
year. It was based on evidence that includes disclosures by a 
senior Soviet defector, blood samples from the North Korean 
soldiers that show smallpox vaccinations and the fairly recent 
manufacture of smallpox vaccine by Iraq, according to the report. 
Officials told the Times that the assessment was an important 
factor in President Clinton's recent decision to reverse course and 
forgo destruction of American stockpiles of the virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Killed in Michigan Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	BINGHAM FARMS, Mich. (AP) -- A psychiatrist who was gunned down  
by a man seeking treatment could have done little to help the 
severely disturbed patient, the doctor's family said Saturday. 
Joseph Brooks Jr., 27, killed Dr. Reuven Bar-Levav and a woman and 
injured four others before killing himself at Bar-Levav's office 
Friday afternoon. One of the wounded remained hospitalized in fair 
condition Saturday. The gunman had been diagnosed elsewhere as a 
paranoid schizophrenic and had come to the office several times, 
said Dr. Leora Bar-Levav. 

</P>
<P>
	Louisiana GOP Wants First Caucus  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) -- Louisiana's Republican leaders decided  
Saturday to hold a 2000 presidential caucus one week ahead of 
Iowa's traditional first-in-the-nation caucus. But the question of 
whether the Republican National Committee would recognize the 
caucus was not addressed by the 160 Republicans who gathered for 
the vote. Instead, the members of the Louisiana GOP spent much of 
the time arguing over and eventually rejecting a competing proposal 
for Louisiana to hold the country's first-ever presidential primary 
with Internet voting. 

</P>
<P>
	South Korea Heightens Attack Alert  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Communist North Korea sent patrol  
boats across a disputed sea border Saturday after threatening to 
attack South Korean warships in contested waters of the Yellow Sea. 
The American-led U.N. Command, which oversees the fragile truce 
between the two bitter rivals, urged North Korea -- for a third time 
this week -- to hold a border military meeting to end the standoff. 
The armed standoff in the Cold War's last flashpoint entered its 
fifth day today, with the two Koreas hardening their stances after 
their ships nearly opened fire yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Pavarotti's Voice Shakes Beirut  
</P>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Beirut, a city torn by war for years,  
shook Saturday night to a different sound -- Luciano Pavarotti's 
voice and the famed tenor's debut in the Arab world was wild. 
Cheers and whistles greeted the Italian when he performed at 
Beirut's Sports City stadium, a site itself symbolizing Beirut's 
wartime death and its postwar recovery. Pavarotti thanked the 
sellout crowd of 20,000 people who, according to organizers, came 
from as far away as Saudi Arabia and Bulgaria. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A.'s Subway Extends to Hollywood  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The 4.6-mile Hollywood extension of the  
city's new subway opened Saturday to huge crowds eager to test the 
new experience of getting around by underground rail instead of by 
car and bus. The premiere of the Hollywood segment marked a major 
step for the much-criticized, over-budget and behind-schedule 
subway. Until today, the Red Line ran just a little over six miles, 
from Union Station across downtown and a short distance to the 
west. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Defeat Sabres 2-1 in Game 3  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Dallas Stars Defeated the Buffalo  
Sabres 2-1 in Game 3 of the Stanley Cup Finals Saturday night. Joe 
Nieuwendyk, almost forced to score with Brett Hull out and Mike 
Modano hampered by a serious wrist injury, had two goals and the 
depleted Stars regained home-ice advantage in the series, taking a 
2-1 edge. The Stars had every reason to lose but didn't, killing 
off eight Buffalo power plays -- one a two-man advantage -- while 
overcoming a groin injury that forced Hull to the locker room after 
less than three minutes of ice time. Hull is eighth in NHL playoff 
history in scoring and had the game-winning goal in Game 2 in 
Dallas. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
