<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Bush WWII Gallery Dedicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDERICKSBURG, Texas (AP) -- The memories weren't all pleasant  
for George Bush as he toured a new museum gallery dedicated to 
World War II battles in the Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw the island over which my roommate was shot down, the  
first casualty of our squadron,'' said the former president, who 
served as a young pilot during the war. ``Saw the island over which 
I was shot down a year later, a few months later, and a lot in 
between.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush cut the ribbon Friday on the George Bush Gallery of the  
National Museum of the Pacific War, part of the larger Admiral 
Nimitz Museum and Historical Center. The museum is named for World 
War II Pacific fleet commander and Fredericksburg native Admiral 
Chester Nimitz, under whom Bush served. 
</P>
<P>
	``This gallery of exciting exhibits will involve younger  
generations in learning about a part of the 20th century that 
shaped human history like no other major event,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among nearly 1,000 artifacts, the gallery has a corn cob pipe  
that belonged to Gen. Douglas MacArthur, a Japanese air ace's 
goggles and a rusty door salvaged from the USS Arizona at Pearl 
Harbor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
