<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Begins Considering Coles Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- International Olympic Committee  
leaders began considering Sunday whether to expel Australian member 
Phil Coles for alleged ethical misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Eager to resolve the case at the start of week-long Olympic  
meetings in Seoul, the IOC executive board decided to deal with the 
Coles issue on the first day rather than Tuesday as originally 
scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, who has already been censured for his role in the Salt  
Lake City scandal, is under investigation for preparing dossiers of 
private information on fellow IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member investigative panel was submitting a report on  
the Coles case to the IOC board Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel could recommend that the case be dropped or that Coles  
be expelled. Any expulsion would have to go to the full IOC 
assembly for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sydney, Coles expressed confidence he would be cleared.  
</P>
<P>
	He told The Sun-Herald newspaper he expected to reclaim his key  
post on the 2000 Sydney Games organizing committee and the 
Australian Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just be glad when all this business is finally put to  
rest,'' he said. ``I'll have more to say when my name is finally 
cleared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles reiterated his contention that he was the victim of a  
political vendetta in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe my name has been turned into a political football  
and I'm talking of people in high places on both sides of state 
politics,'' Coles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, who has steadfastly refused pressure to resign, has been  
questioned three times by IOC investigators for alleged abuse of 
his office. 
</P>
<P>
	After appearing last week before a special panel in Lausanne,  
Switzerland, Coles said he was convinced he'd proven his innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, a former Olympic rower who has been an IOC member for 17  
years, received a ``most severe warning'' from the IOC in March for 
accepting lavish travel and other incentives from Salt Lake 
bidders. His case was left open amid further allegations of abusing 
his IOC status. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles' ex-wife told the IOC the couple received jewelry valued  
at $6,000 from a businessman associated with the Athens bid for the 
1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest investigation centered on more recent allegations  
that Coles had compiled secret dossiers on IOC members for Sydney's 
successful 2000 bid and passed them on to Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Pal Schmitt, an IOC vice president, has accused Coles of  
breaking ``unwritten ethical rules'' and acting ``against the 
dignity, the pride of IOC members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not how an IOC member should behave,'' Schmitt said.  
</P>
<P>
	But Dick Pound, another IOC vice president and a personal friend  
of Coles, dismissed the dossiers as ``normal chit-chat'' among bid 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's done all the time,'' Pound told The Associated  
Press last week. ``You go at this candidate city business the same 
way. You analyze your electorate, figure out which are more likely 
to vote for you, and how to convince those who are least likely. 
You pass around and share intelligence. I think candidate cities 
even do it among themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC officials decided to deal with the Coles case early so it  
doesn't overshadow the rest of the week's meetings -- including 
Saturday's selection of the host city for the 2006 Winter Games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 12:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
