<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops in Shooting May Be Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) -- A lawyer for four white police officers  
involved in the controversial shooting death of a 19-year-old black 
woman says the Police Department is preparing to fire them. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers ``are clearly devastated and frustrated'' with the  
decision, said Bill Hadden, who is representing the officers. He 
told the Press-Enterprise of Riverside that his clients are 
``political scapegoats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting of Tyisha Miller at a gas station last Dec. 28  
prompted complaints of excessive force and racial discrimination. 
After being summoned by a distress call, the officers fired 23 
shots at Miller, hitting her 12 times as she sat in her car outside 
the station. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say Miller had a gun on her lap and was unresponsive as  
she sat reclined in the driver's seat. One officer said Miller 
reached for the weapon as officers broke the car's driver's side 
window in an effort to remove it. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the Riverside County district attorney's office declined  
to file criminal charges against the officers, saying that the 
officers may have made tactical errors but there was no evidence of 
criminal intent. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Justice and the state attorney general's  
office continue to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Chief Jerry Carroll confirmed an internal affairs  
investigation into the case has been completed. He declined to 
discuss the findings but told The Associated Press he agreed with 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll has previously defended the officers' actions, saying  
police sometimes must use deadly force to defend themselves. On 
Friday, he reiterated his support for them not to be prosecuted. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers have been on paid administrative leave.  
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Roth, a lawyer for Miller's family, questioned the length  
of time taken in preparing the 4,500-page report. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what we know about the case, there's more than enough  
evidence to support a finding that these officers grossly violated 
proper police procedures,'' Roth said. The family has filed a 
federal civil rights lawsuit against the city and several officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some family members were pleased with the report but said it  
does not resolve the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long way from justice, but it's a step forward,'' said  
Miller's aunt, Minerva Butler. ``This is not a celebration. It's 
not even a victory. It's not victory until it's over, when they are 
behind bars.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
