<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton, Mrs.Gore on Their Own </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Seven years after they boarded the  
Clinton-Gore campaign bus together, Hillary Rodham Clinton and 
Tipper Gore are nearing the end of a shared political road, each 
preparing to step out on her own. 
</P>
<P>
	Their interests, tied together by their husbands' campaigns to  
win and then retain the White House, will be diverging in coming 
months. Mrs. Clinton is exploring a U.S. Senate run, and Mrs. Gore 
could succeed Mrs. Clinton as first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday they made the kind of double-barreled appearance that  
has become rarer over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Women for Gore 2000 fund-raiser, they strode onto a stage  
to the strains of ``Don't You Love Her Madly?'' which was nearly 
drowned out by applause. 
</P>
<P>
	They drew standing ovations and hugged when Mrs. Clinton  
introduced the woman who hopes to succeed her in the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	They basked in political plugs from California first lady Sharon  
Davis, U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer and U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters. 
</P>
<P>
	They then showered each other with praise.  
</P>
<P>
	``She has been role model for so many of us,'' Mrs. Clinton  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some associates and other observers say the dual appearances  
were bound to taper off. They have become more infrequent over the 
years for Mrs. Gore and Mrs. Clinton, said Marsha Berry, a 
spokeswoman for Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'd find that they split up to use resources in different  
parts of they country as much as they could, so it's not often that 
you see them doing fund-raising events together,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, ``they've made a commitment as a team and they remain  
one,'' Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, though she spent part of last week testing the waters  
for her own possible candidacy in New York, Mrs. Clinton flew to 
California to raise money for Gore's presidential bid. Earlier this 
month, both appeared at a Washington, D.C., event to rally women to 
Gore's effort. 
</P>
<P>
	A second appearance in Northern California on Saturday brought  
in donations for the Women's Leadership Forum, a Democratic Party 
arm. Mrs. Gore and Mrs. Clinton addressed the same group in San 
Francisco during their husbands' 1996 re-election campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	They found common ground as advocates for children's issues,  
despite their disparate backgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore set aside a career as a child psychologist to raise  
her four children. Mrs. Clinton, a mother of one, was a partner in 
a prestigious law firm and member of corporate boards. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years ago next month, they barnstormed the country after  
the Democratic National Convention. On Saturday, they recalled the 
hectic 1992 bus tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had that kind of adventure ever since,'' Mrs. Clinton  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 13:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summary of Century's Major Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A jostling mob of journalists swarmed the courthouse.  
Photographers snapped away. This murder trial would be ``reported 
to the ends of the civilized globe,'' one paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendant was a millionaire. The motive was jealous rage.  
The crime was bloody. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the Trial of the Century -- and it was only 1907.  
</P>
<P>
	The defendant was Harry Thaw (O.J. Simpson would not be born for  
40 years), and the case set a pattern for ``trials of the century'' 
to come. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 33 cases have been given that label, according to  
Gerald Uelman, professor of law at Santa Clara University Law 
School. 
</P>
<P>
	American schoolchildren learn the pledge of ``Justice for all,''  
but these cases show how difficult it is to keep that promise. War 
crimes, civil rights abuses, sensational murder and assassinations. 
Even the impeachment of a president. All of these have been placed 
at the doorstep of the law in this century. And not all have 
resulted in fair verdicts. 
</P>
<P>
	The most powerful cases forced society to face fundamental  
quandaries. In the Scopes ``Monkey Trial,'' it was the place of 
religion in public life. The Simpson case presented troubling 
racial questions. Trials like the Lindbergh baby kidnapping and 
Charles Manson's ``Helter Skelter'' killings left us peering into 
the darkness of the soul. 
</P>
<P>
	``The measure of a great trial,'' said defense attorney Leslie  
Abramson, ``should be the impact on society -- cases that advanced 
our state of knowledge and reflected on the problems of the times, 
those that aided in the search for truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie Levenson, associate dean of Loyola Law School in Los  
Angeles, offered another standard. 
</P>
<P>
	``A trial of the century is when the public feels invested in  
the outcome,'' she said. ``They will sit around and talk about it; 
they'll root for one side or the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Here's a look at some of the 20th century's greatest dramas of  
crime and punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *'RED VELVET SWING'   	
</P>
<P>
	Harry Thaw, the wastrel heir to a Pittsburgh industrialist's  
fortune, fatally shot society architect Stanford White in the 
middle of the White-designed Madison Square Garden in view of 
hundreds. Thaw's wife, showgirl Evelyn Nesbit, had told her husband 
that White, her former lover, once raped her. 
</P>
<P>
	The first ``trial of the century'' offered salacious views of  
the upper crust. There was testimony about White's red velvet swing 
where he liked to have showgirls swing so he could look underneath 
their dresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Great defenses often make great trials, and Thaw's lawyer,  
Delphin Delmas, had a winner. His client, he said, suffered from 
``Dementia Americana,'' an affliction of the American male whose 
wife's purity is violated. After two trials, Thaw was found 
innocent by reason of insanity and spent the rest of his life in 
and out of insane asylums. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial, held in New York, taught the media lessons they would  
not forget about the appeal of courtroom dramas featuring wealth, 
indulgence and sexual decadence. It was the beginning of saturation 
coverage with the new art of photographic reproduction enlivening 
newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FATTY ARBUCKLE   	
</P>
<P>
	The 1921 trial of Fatty Arbuckle, a comic superstar in the  
fledgling movie industry, focused on loose morals in Hollywood. 
Arbuckle was charged with manslaughter when an actress died after a 
wild party. There were allegations that rape by the overweight 
actor had killed her. Two juries deadlocked and a third acquitted 
Arbuckle, declaring a great injustice had been done. Nonetheless, 
his career was ruined. 
</P>
<P>
	More important, the nation's moral outrage led to creation of  
the movie industry's Hays Office, which censored films for the next 
30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SACCO AND VANZETTI   	
</P>
<P>
	Rarely has an outpouring of public outrage equaled that at the  
conviction and execution of Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian immigrant anarchists, a shoemaker and a fish  
peddler, were charged with committing murder during a $15,000 
payroll robbery in South Braintree, Mass. Many said their political 
views were on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge was denounced as prejudiced against them, and the 1921  
trial was called unfair. A Who's Who of intellectuals protested in 
poems, books and paintings. There were general strikes on behalf of 
the men worldwide. American embassies were stoned and one was 
bombed. 
</P>
<P>
	The two went to their deaths declaring their innocence. In 1977,  
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis issued a proclamation clearing 
their names. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SCOPES 'MONKEY TRIAL'   	
</P>
<P>
	If great lawyers make great trials, the ``Monkey Trial'' of John  
Thomas Scopes in Dayton, Tenn., in 1925 matched two giants. 
</P>
<P>
	For the defense, Clarence Darrow brought a brilliant mind, a  
fighting spirit and the luster of participation just a year before 
in another ``trial of the century,'' that of Nathan Leopold and 
Richard Loeb in the ``thrill killing'' of a 12-year-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining the prosecution was none other than populist  
ex-presidential candidate and orator William Jennings Bryan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Scopes trial, fictionalized in the drama, ``Inherit The  
Wind,'' involved a young science teacher charged with teaching the 
theory of evolution in violation of a Tennessee law that permitted 
only the Bible's version of divine creation. It was a classic 
battle between fundamentalism and scientific skepticism. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, as Darrow badgered Bryan, whom he had called to  
testify as an expert on Scripture, a prosecutor objected: What was 
the purpose of the questioning? 
</P>
<P>
	``The purpose is to cast ridicule on everybody who believes in  
the Bible,'' Bryan snapped, drawing applause. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrow fired back: ``We have the purpose of preventing bigots  
and ignoramuses from controlling the education of the United 
States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scopes' guilty verdict and fine of $100 were later overturned.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE SCOTTSBORO BOYS   	
</P>
<P>
	Racial prejudice was the unspoken topic in the Scottsboro Boys  
trials which stretched over six years, 1931-1937, in Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine young black men, the oldest 19 and the youngest 12, were  
charged with raping two white women aboard a train. The women were 
revealed to be prostitutes, and two doctors testified they had not 
been raped. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Communist Party declared the case ``a legal  
lynching.'' Defense lawyer Samuel Liebowitz required National Guard 
protection during the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	All defendants were convicted and sentenced to death. The U.S.  
Supreme Court overturned the convictions because blacks were 
excluded from the jury, a landmark decision. Ultimately, four of 
the Scottsboro defendants served prison sentences. The last 
survivor was pardoned at age 64 in 1976 by Alabama Gov. George C. 
Wallace. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LINDBERGH KIDNAPPING   	
</P>
<P>
	The 1935 trial of Bruno Richard Hauptmann, charged with the  
kidnapping and murder of Charles Lindbergh's infant child, was 
``the biggest story since the Resurrection,'' H.L. Mencken wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindbergh electrified the world in 1927 by flying solo from New  
York to Paris . The snatching of his 20-month-old son from his crib 
was every parent's worst nightmare. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-year manhunt led authorities to Hauptmann, a German-born  
carpenter. Investigators found $14,500 in ransom money behind 
boards in his garage. Unusual scientific analysis of wood linked 
him to a ladder found below the nursery window. Hauptmann was 
convicted and electrocuted in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial drew one of the largest press corps in history.  
Newsreel cameras were allowed in court for the first time. Tourists 
flocked to the Flemington, N.J., courthouse, and souvenir salesmen 
hawked tiny replicas of the kidnap ladder. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NUREMBERG TRIALS   	
</P>
<P>
	It would become an infamous defense: They were just following  
orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly two dozen men who helped run Adolf Hitler's Third Reich  
and carry out the Holocaust were brought to the dock in November 
1945. Their war crimes, said Robert H. Jackson, the U.S. Supreme 
Court justice who served as chief prosecutor, were ``so malignant 
... that civilization cannot tolerate their being ignored, because 
it cannot survive their being repeated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some objected that the vanquished in war could not receive a  
fair trial from the victors, but the International Military 
Tribunal went forward in the German city of Nuremberg, where masses 
had once saluted the fuehrer at rallies. The evidence was 
overwhelming and often heartbreaking. At one point, a graphic film 
of the dead in concentration camps sent the judges filing out 
without adjourning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, all but three defendants were convicted. Ten were  
hanged. Hermann Goering, also sentenced to death, managed to commit 
suicide, as Hitler had done. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROSENBERGS AND THE BOMB   	
</P>
<P>
	The nuclear age and Cold War hysteria converged in the 1951  
trial of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a case infected by 
anti-Semitism. The Rosenbergs, former Communist Party members, were 
charged with passing secrets of the atom bomb to the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	When they were electrocuted in 1953, New York's Union Square  
filled with 10,000 protesters and rallies erupted around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Historians debate their guilt today, and their sons still press  
for their vindication. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SAM SHEPPARD   	
</P>
<P>
	Two trials a decade apart put Sam Sheppard's name in legal  
history books. His sensational 1954 murder case came to symbolize 
pretrial prejudice and the impact of adverse media publicity. 
Attorney F. Lee Bailey gained fame by winning a U.S. Supreme Court 
reversal of Sheppard's conviction in the stabbing murder of his 
wife, Marilyn. 
</P>
<P>
	The saga of the Cleveland osteopath, who won acquittal in 1966,  
inspired the TV series, ``The Fugitive.'' His son recently 
presented new evidence, seeking to prove definitively that his 
father was innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHICAGO 7   	
</P>
<P>
	Seven protesters were tried together for incitement to riot at  
the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago, where police 
and opponents of American military involvement in Vietnam battled 
in the streets. The courtroom antics of the defendants and the 
judge, Julius Hoffman, made the trial almost as tumultuous. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffman ordered an eighth defendant, Black Panther Bobby Seale,  
bound, gagged and tied to his courtroom chair. He was tried 
separately. Hoffman issued some 200 contempt citations against the 
defendants and most of their attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	The courtroom became a theater of protest as wild-haired  
defendants wore judicial robes to court, then stripped them off and 
stomped on them. 
</P>
<P>
	Five defendants were convicted of inciting to riot, and Seale of  
contempt. All convictions were overturned. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MANSON TRIAL   	
</P>
<P>
	The story of Charles Manson and his band of ``hippie'' followers  
strained credulity. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, no one knew what was behind the 1969 murders of  
actress Sharon Tate and six others in the hills near Hollywood, a 
fearsome spectacle of butchered bodies and bloody scrawlings on 
mansion walls. ``Helter Skelter'' was one chillingly mysterious 
message. 
</P>
<P>
	When Manson's gang was rounded up, terror turned to disbelief. A  
demented cult leader had ordered mass murders on a whim, 
prosecutors said. The 10-month trial revealed a world of 
disaffected young runaways -- remnants of the '60s culture of flower 
power, LSD and sexual anarchy -- who killed on command. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Manson's ``family'' camped outside the courthouse  
during the 10-month trial. Manson and his three women followers 
carved the letter ``X'' in their foreheads, and once Manson leaped 
at the judge, shouting, ``Someone should cut your head off, old 
man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manson and the women were sentenced to death, later commuted to  
life imprisonment when the death penalty was briefly outlawed. In 
subsequent years, the women expressed remorse. Manson, still in 
prison, was asked on a TV show whether he was crazy. ``Yeah, I'm 
crazy,'' he said. ``But that used to count for something. Now 
everybody's crazy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PENTAGON PAPERS   	
</P>
<P>
	The case put the Vietnam War on trial.  
</P>
<P>
	It began when a top military analyst, Daniel Ellsberg,  
disillusioned with American policy, decided to release a 
top-secret, 47-volume Defense Department study of the U.S. role in 
Indochina over three decades. His action was branded by President 
Nixon as treason. 
</P>
<P>
	The government tried to stop publication of the Pentagon Papers,  
first in The New York Times and then in The Washington Post, 
prompting a landmark Supreme Court decision barring prior restraint 
of free expression. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsberg and his colleague, Anthony Russo, went on trial in 1971  
in Los Angeles, where the papers had been copied. 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon authorized unlawful efforts to discredit Ellsberg,  
including a break-in at his psychiatrist's office. Details of the 
burglary opened another Pandora's box of information on the 
emerging Watergate scandal, which eventually toppled Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, charges against Ellsberg and Russo were dismissed on  
grounds of outrageous governmental misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *O.J. SIMPSON   	
</P>
<P>
	When Simpson, a football hero and pop culture star, was arrested  
for the gruesome stabbings of his ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, 
and her friend, Ronald Goldman, it was a made-for-TV tragedy from 
the start. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson had been a familiar face on screen for years. When he  
fled in a white Bronco, TV cameras followed. His one-year trial was 
televised gavel to gavel. Viewers were transfixed by legal 
procedure and such esoterica as DNA. The subtexts of racial 
prejudice and domestic violence were dissected by a new breed of TV 
personalities -- legal commentators. 
</P>
<P>
	When the trial ended in acquittal many who disagreed chose to  
blame the cameras. A later civil trial, untelevised, resulted in 
Simpson being held liable for the killings. Simpson has 
consistently claimed innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	Did he do it? The answer is left to history.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLINTON IMPEACHMENT TRIAL   	
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's impeachment trial in 1998 was a trial of the  
century with no live witnesses, no traditional rules of evidence, 
no presumptionf innocence or standard of reasonable doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a political exercise, but it did have the elements of a  
sensational court case: a celebrity defendant, a beautiful woman, 
illicit sex and power. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Senate's decision not to convict will be argued well  
into the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Linda Deutsch has covered major trials for three  
decades, among them Manson, the Pentagon Papers and Simpson. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Chief Visits Queens Alma Mater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CIA chief George Tenet visited his old high  
school in New York City and let slip a couple of secrets about his 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the biggest mouth in town. Nobody believed I could keep  
a secret,'' he told students and teachers at Benjamin Cardozo High 
School in Queens on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tenet and his twin brother, William, a cardiologist, were named  
``Alumnus of the Year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to tell you that I've learned my lessons. I'm very very  
discreet now,'' said Tenet, who graduated from the school in 1970 
and was named head of the intelligence agency in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	He credited his high school soccer coach, Ed Tatarian, as an  
important influence whose wisdom still helps him when he's in a jam 
-- and who he says taught him how to run an organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``My high school soccer coach taught me more about how to run a  
big organization of people, as I look back on it, than anybody ever 
taught me for the rest of my life,'' said Tenet. ``He really taught 
me a lot about values, how to conduct yourself, sticking by your 
guns. He was a really giant figure in my life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Irvine Leads Formula One Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- As if the Ferraris's weren't fast enough  
already. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Irvine led the way and teammate Michael Schumacher was  
third on Friday in the opening practice sessions for the Canadian 
Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Italian team is introducing a new version of its  
powerful engine in time for today's qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the evolutionary new power plant, Irvine smiled and  
replied: ``It's only a little bit better and a little bit faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine, third in the points behind Schumacher and defending  
series champion Mika Hakkinen, got around the 2.747-mile, 13-turn 
Circuit Gilles Villeneuve in 1 minute, 20.576 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I only made one mistake and I was pleased with myself until  
then,'' Irvine said, referring to a harmless spin in the afternoon 
session. ``My last lap should have been my best, but I used too 
much of the curb at one point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine's time was .700 seconds quicker than the 1:20.664 by  
McLaren-Mercedes driver David Coulthard of Scotland -- last year's 
Canadian pole-winner -- and .934 seconds faster than Schumacher's 
1:21.276. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher, the defending race winner, was very confident after  
Friday's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to the new engine,'' he said. ``I expect  
we will be very competitive in qualifying and in the race, as this 
circuit suits our car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Alesi, the 1995 Canada winner, was fourth overall at  
1:21.510 in a Sauber-Petronas, followed by Giancarlo Fisichella's 
Benetton-Playlife at 1:21.724. 
</P>
<P>
	Riccardo Zonta, a 23-year-old Brazilian, made an impressive  
return to action following a three-race layoff while recuperating 
from a broken foot. The youngster put his British American Racing 
entry sixth at 1:21.810, beating out Hakkinen, who struggled to a 
1:21.950 in the other Team McLaren entry. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen, who trails Schumacher by six points in the battle for  
the 1999 series title, does not enjoy racing on the Canadian 
circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This track is just weird,'' the Finnish driver said. ``I've  
never got it right, to be honest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a challenge. If I get it right, I'll be very  
pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even further off pace than Hakkinen was Team Williams driver  
Alex Zanardi, the CART champion each of the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Zanardi, who was an immediate star when he joined the  
American-based series in 1996, has struggled badly so far in his 
return to Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's practice, Zanardi was 18th at 1:23.824.  
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly miss the competitiveness of the car I had  
underneath me last year (in CART),'' the Italian driver said. ``But 
having said that, the Winfield-Williams team is a great 
organization and nobody on the team is happy with the performance 
of the car right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have something to learn about driving the car on these  
grooved tires, which is the feature that has changed the handling 
of the cars most dramatically since I was last in F1 (in 1994).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Villeneuve, another former CART champion and Zonta's BAR  
teammate, was ninth at 1:22.021 -- a performance the Canadian-born 
local favorite considered mediocre. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're finding some things out to make the car better, but it's  
very difficult,'' Villeneuve said. ``Riccardo's position is 
encouraging for the team as a whole ... so it's looking good.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Irvine Leads Formula One Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- As if the Ferraris's weren't fast enough  
already. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Irvine led the way and teammate Michael Schumacher was  
third on Friday in the opening practice sessions for the Canadian 
Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Italian team is introducing a new version of its  
powerful engine in time for today's qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the evolutionary new power plant, Irvine smiled and  
replied: ``It's only a little bit better and a little bit faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine, third in the points behind Schumacher and defending  
series champion Mika Hakkinen, got around the 2.747-mile, 13-turn 
Circuit Gilles Villeneuve in 1 minute, 20.576 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I only made one mistake and I was pleased with myself until  
then,'' Irvine said, referring to a harmless spin in the afternoon 
session. ``My last lap should have been my best, but I used too 
much of the curb at one point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine's time was .700 seconds quicker than the 1:20.664 by  
