Canadian pole-winner -- and .934 seconds faster than Schumacher's 
1:21.276. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher, the defending race winner, was very confident after  
Friday's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to the new engine,'' he said. ``I expect  
we will be very competitive in qualifying and in the race, as this 
circuit suits our car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Alesi, the 1995 Canada winner, was fourth overall at  
1:21.510 in a Sauber-Petronas, followed by Giancarlo Fisichella's 
Benetton-Playlife at 1:21.724. 
</P>
<P>
	Riccardo Zonta, a 23-year-old Brazilian, made an impressive  
return to action following a three-race layoff while recuperating 
from a broken foot. The youngster put his British American Racing 
entry sixth at 1:21.810, beating out Hakkinen, who struggled to a 
1:21.950 in the other Team McLaren entry. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen, who trails Schumacher by six points in the battle for  
the 1999 series title, does not enjoy racing on the Canadian 
circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This track is just weird,'' the Finnish driver said. ``I've  
never got it right, to be honest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a challenge. If I get it right, I'll be very  
pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even further off pace than Hakkinen was Team Williams driver  
Alex Zanardi, the CART champion each of the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Zanardi, who was an immediate star when he joined the  
American-based series in 1996, has struggled badly so far in his 
return to Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's practice, Zanardi was 18th at 1:23.824.  
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly miss the competitiveness of the car I had  
underneath me last year (in CART),'' the Italian driver said. ``But 
having said that, the Winfield-Williams team is a great 
organization and nobody on the team is happy with the performance 
of the car right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have something to learn about driving the car on these  
grooved tires, which is the feature that has changed the handling 
of the cars most dramatically since I was last in F1 (in 1994).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Villeneuve, another former CART champion and Zonta's BAR  
teammate, was ninth at 1:22.021 -- a performance the Canadian-born 
local favorite considered mediocre. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're finding some things out to make the car better, but it's  
very difficult,'' Villeneuve said. ``Riccardo's position is 
encouraging for the team as a whole ... so it's looking good.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
