<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Stops Sharing Customer Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Two days after Minnesota sued U.S. Bank  
for selling customer data to telemarketers, the nation's largest 
bank announced it will stop sharing the information with marketing 
firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our customers consider the personal and financial information  
we maintain about them highly confidential,'' Ken Lewis, president 
of Bank of America, said Friday. ``This is the right thing to do 
for our customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota Attorney General Mike Hatch accused U.S. Bank of  
selling sensitive data ranging from customer names, Social Security 
numbers, birth dates, credit limits, marital status, occupation and 
home ownership status. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America officials said the decision was not prompted by  
the Minnesota lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been looking at re-engineering these processes for four  
or five weeks now,'' said bank spokesman John Cleghorn. ``We 
thought this was the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new policy, the bank will not share any customer  
information with marketers who offer their products and services to 
Bank of America customers, Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, the bank will not enable telemarketers to  
call its customers offering products unrelated to their financial 
needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America, with $614 billion in assets, has branches in 22  
states and the District of Columbia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 10:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maine Town May Again Host President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) -- Marine One thundering overhead. The  
presidential motorcade snaking down Ocean Avenue. Noisy critics 
dressed like broccoli spears demonstrating on the Village Green. 
</P>
<P>
	The heady days when Kennebunkport played host to a sitting  
president are becoming a distant memory. Now, former President 
George Bush can play golf or take his boat onto the ocean without 
being in the public eye. 
</P>
<P>
	But the presidential aspirations of a younger Bush, who visits  
this weekend, have residents wondering if the quiet resort town on 
Maine's rocky coast might once again play host to a sitting 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents are generally enthusiastic about Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner. He will spend 
Sunday with his parents at Walker's Point before visiting New 
Hampshire, home of the first presidential primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think the people in Maine are behind him,'' said Dawn  
Patten, who runs Patten's Berry Farm, behind the Cape Arundel Golf 
Club where father and son golf. ``I think the people like him. I'll 
vote with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bushes go way back in Kennebunkport. The three-story,  
stone-and-shingle home at Walker's Point has been in the family 
since the turn of the century, and the former president has spent 
every summer there since boyhood except when he served as a Navy 
aviator in World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	George and Barbara Bush have been around long enough to be part  
of the landscape. And they're known as down-to-earth people. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the best part, they aren't hoity-toity,'' said Robert  
Fischer, as he mixed lobster meat and mayonnaise to make lobster 
rolls at Mabel's, a small restaurant where the Bushes often eat. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Bush is a big fan of Fischer's peanut butter ice cream  
pie, and he buys ice cream by the tub for his grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	He also has a hankering for Patten's fresh-squeezed orange juice  
and has a cold glassful after playing golf at the golf club, where 
he is a fixture when he is in town. He takes time to pose for 
pictures, which are posted in many stores around town. He signed a 
golf ball for one of Patten's workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Even people who don't know the Bushes get a friendly wave from  
the former president when he walks by. 
</P>
<P>
	It's no surprise that the warmth shown by George and Barbara  
Bush toward the community is returned to their family. And the 
warmness crosses party lines, even though Republicans outnumber 
Democrats roughly 2-to-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've met the president and he's a very kindhearted person. It  
would be nice to see the legacy continue both in Kennebunkport and 
the White House,'' said Laura Lee Burke, who works at the desk at 
the Yachtsman, where Bush docks his boat, the Fidelity II. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years after Bush left office, many residents seem to have  
forgotten the unpleasant, disruptive things like traffic congestion 
and demonstrations. Instead, they remember the good things, like 
the excitement of hosting world leaders such as French President 
Francois Mitterand, British Prime Minister John Major and Jordon's 
King Hussein. 
</P>
<P>
	Town Manager Jane Duncan recalls how Mitterand's visit coincided  
with the Masabesic High School senior prom, which was held at the 
same waterfront hotel where he was staying. The students declined 
to cancel their big night but invited him to join them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the French secret service standing around and kids in  
their tuxedos and prom dresses,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, thoughts of the presidential limelight shining twice  
on Kennebunkport are premature. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if George W. Bush won the Republican Party's nomination and  
then the general election, it's not a sure thing that he would be a 
frequent visitor to Kennebunkport. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Texas governor typically visits Walker's Point with  
his family in August, he prefers to go fishing at his own vacation 
home on a lake in eastern Texas, said Mindy Tucker, Bush's campaign 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given his druthers, he'd prefer to be on a lake bass  
fishing,'' Ms. Tucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	But some still hold out hope of hosting another president, even  
if only occasionally. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Shawmut Inn, General Manager Roger Sibley has rented 55  
rooms this weekend to reporters covering George W. Bush. That's 
almost as many rooms as when he used to accommodate the White House 
press corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounding as if he had given some thought to another Bush in the  
White House, Sibley noted that the wiring was still in place to 
transform some office space back into a press filing center. Even 
the underground cables that ABC, CBS, NBC and CNN used for live 
shots in front of the ocean remain in place, Sibley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we could do it again like there was never a break  
between 1992 and 2000,'' he said. ``Yeah, we could do it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Orioles Bench Belle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Sports Writer	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Baltimore's Albert Belle did not play Friday    	
against the Braves after a shouting match with Orioles manager Ray  
Miller, ending the outfielder's streak of 392 consecutive games 
played. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, who was baseball's active leader in consecutive games  
played, was replaced in right field by Jeff Conine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just came in and saw the lineup,'' said Conine, who went  
3-for-5 in Baltimore's 6-2 victory. ``That's all I want to say 
about it. It's a sensitive issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Belle and Miller have declined to comment on the incident,  
which occurred during Wednesday night's 4-2 victory over the 
Florida Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albert Belle just didn't play tonight,'' Miller said. ``That's  
all I've got to say on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said he preferred to keep the focus on Sidney Ponson, who  
pitched a five-hitter to beat Greg Maddux and the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to talk about Albert Belle when we just had a  
guy pitch an outstanding game,'' the manager said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller indicated before the game that Belle would return to the  
lineup Saturday, but he wouldn't address the issue after. ``We'll 
see about that when the lineup goes up tomorrow,'' the manager 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle came out on the field to congratulate his teammates after  
the game and, according to Miller, ``He was in the dugout shaking 
hands with everybody the whole game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Belle declined to speak with reporters.  
</P>
<P>
	Belle, who has gone through a disappointing season, failed to  
run out a ground ball in the top of the ninth Wednesday night, 
completing an 0-for-5 game. 
</P>
<P>
	In the bottom of the inning, Miller replaced Belle in the  
outfield with Rich Amaral, a move the manager said he planned to 
make before Belle's groundout. But the temperamental slugger was 
unaware of the move until he was on his way to his outfield 
position, eventually jogging back to the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	In the dugout, TV cameras caught an exchange of profanities  
between Miller and Belle. Belle yelled angrily at Miller and was 
restrained by teammate Jeff Reboulet. Miller waved Belle off with a 
toss of his hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, who signed a $65 million, five-year contract with  
Baltimore in December, has been suspended six times during his 
career and his disdain of the media is well known. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle was hitting only .244 with one home run in his previous 21  
games. The Orioles, with a $78.5 million opening-day payroll, are 
the most disappointing team in baseball with a 22-36 record, and 
there has been speculation that Miller's job is in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's Vinny Castilla now has the longest active streak of  
consecutive games -- 304 including Friday night's game at Texas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
