<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians 4, Reds 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Charles Nagy won his fifth consecutive start  
and the Cleveland Indians' bullpen narrowly escaped a couple of 
late Cincinnati threats tonight, preserving a 4-3 win over the 
Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Alomar hit his first homer in nearly a month to put the  
Indians ahead to stay and set up their second straight win over 
their intrastate rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Nagy (8-3) overcame homers by Greg Vaughn and Eddie Taubensee --  
the only ones he has allowed during the five-game winning streak -- 
then watched the bullpen frustrate the Reds twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliever Ricardo Rincon provided the game's most electrifying  
moment when he loaded the bases with a couple of two-out walks in 
the seventh to bring up Sean Casey, hitting .382. 
</P>
<P>
	As fans chanted his last name in unison, Casey -- the first  
baseman who came from Cleveland in a trade last year -- flew out to 
David Justice on the warning track in left field. 
</P>
<P>
	There was another close call in the eighth, when Barry Larkin  
drew a walk from Paul Shuey and stole second and third. Hal Morris' 
sharp grounder up the middle deflected off Shuey's pitching hand to 
Alomar, who threw to first for the final out. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Jackson pitched the ninth for his 13th save in 14 chances.  
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 52,804 was equally divided in loyalties for a  
second consecutive night. Thousands of Indians fans provided the 
Reds with their first regular-season sellout this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar drew an ovation from half of the crowd with a two-run  
homer off Pete Harnisch (5-6) that put the Indians ahead to stay 
4-2 in the fifth inning. It was Alomar's seventh of the season and 
his first since May 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians have won four of their five games at Cinergy Field  
in the last two seasons. Harnisch is the only pitcher to stop them 
there, outpitching Nagy for a 2-1 win in the series opener last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nagy got the better of the matchup this time, holding the Reds  
to five hits in 6 1-3 innings. Two of the hits were solo homers of 
opposite extremes -- Vaughn hit one into the upper deck in the 
second inning and Taubensee hit one that deflected off the top of 
the wall in the seventh, cutting the lead to 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn's 14th homer was only the 27th to reach the upper deck in  
the stadium's 29-year history. The 428-foot shot landed in the 
first section inside the left-field foul screen and ended Nagy's 
streak of 30 2-3 innings without giving up a homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Taubensee's homer in the seventh barely eluded Justice's glove  
and bounced off the top of the wall, extending his hitting streak 
to a career-high 15 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch had to leave his start last Sunday in Kansas City after  
only 1 2-3 innings because of a sore shoulder. He seemed fine 
Saturday, striking out seven in six innings. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Alomar was ejected in the ninth by Bruce Dreckman for  
arguing ball-and-strike calls. The Indians played the rest of the 
game under protest. ... Jim Thome was out of the Indians' lineup 
Saturday and won't start Sunday. Manager Mike Hargrove is giving 
him some time off to try to help him break out of a slump. Thome 
pinch hit in the ninth and singled to break an 0-for-19 slump. ... 
Nagy struck out in all three at-bats, leaving him 1-for-13 career 
at the plate. ... Reliever Mark Wohlers will start a rehabilitation 
assignment with one of the Reds' minor league teams next week. 
Wohlers is on the DL with anxiety disorder. ... Vaughn also homered 
into the upper deck with San Diego two years ago. He's one of six 
players to hit more than one into the red seats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
