<DOCNO> APW19990612.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:49:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Airlines Hit With Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A man injured in last week's deadly American  
Airlines crash has filed a lawsuit claiming the airline trained its 
pilots in unsafe cockpit practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Pennington, 44, was aboard American Airlines Flight 1420 on  
June 1 when the plane sped off a runway while landing at the Little 
Rock, Ark., airport and crashed into the steel posts of a catwalk. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people, including Capt. Richard Buschmann, died and more  
than 80 were injured when the plane broke up and caught fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Friday in a Dallas County district court,  
contends Buschmann and a co-pilot did not follow a landing 
checklist, including failing to arm the landing spoilers. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit -- which does not specify damages -- blames American  
Airlines and its parent company, AMR Corp., for adopting ``policies 
and practices which were contrary to safe cockpit resource 
management.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines spokesman Chris Chiames said he found it  
``curious'' that lawyers have determined the cause of the accident 
before the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other lawsuits have been filed regarding the crash,  
including one filed in Little Rock by the family of Debra Sattari 
of Vallejo, Calif., who died in the accident. The lawsuit claims 
the airline was negligent for trying to land the plane in a storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors in Chicago and Little Rock also have sued American.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
