<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 03:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baptists Trying To Broaden Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAKE FOREST, N.C. (AP) -- The president of the Southern Baptist  
Convention will propose that the denomination broaden its appeal to 
the nation's inner cities by founding multiethnic congregations 
from Boston to Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan from Rev. Paige Patterson marks a dramatic shift for a  
denomination whose 16 million members live mostly in the suburbs, 
small towns and rural areas. It is to be presented next week at the 
group's annual meeting in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's desperation in the inner city,'' said Patterson, who  
is also president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in 
Wake Forest. ``There are people there who have never experienced 
love and compassion, who don't know where their next meal is coming 
from. We cannot afford, knowing we will stand before God, to 
neglect these masses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patterson, the architect of the denomination's conservative  
resurgence, will share the stage with Reggie White. The retired 
football legend and ordained Baptist minister is expected to 
address traditional family values. 
</P>
<P>
	The denomination, formed in 1845 by rural whites who insisted on  
their right to own slaves, has never before focused so sharply on 
diversity. Throughout the civil rights era, blacks were not welcome 
in most Southern Baptist churches. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, the denomination apologized to blacks for years  
of tolerating racism. It now has an estimated 2,800 churches with 
mostly black members -- a tiny sliver of the thousands of black 
Baptist churches affiliated with other conventions. 
</P>
<P>
	Patterson will propose creating 180 churches in six cities over  
the next three years. Next year, efforts will be focused on Chicago 
and Phoenix. Boston and Las Vegas will follow in 2001, and 
Philadelphia and Seattle in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	In each city, a full-time coordinator will work with volunteers  
in nearby Baptist churches and associations. Initial efforts will 
include Bible studies and prayer groups before a church is founded. 
</P>
<P>
	Scholars say demographics may be one reason for the plan.  
</P>
<P>
	``The average white Southern Baptist is 50 years old,'' said  
Bill Leonard, dean of the divinity school at Wake Forest University 
and a Baptist historian. ``They've pretty much saturated the 
suburbs, and they know the fastest-growing population is 
nonwhite.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
