<HEADLINE> Switched Babies Case Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The restraining order obtained by the  
husband of Kimberly Mays Weeks, who was switched at birth and 
became embroiled in a bitter custody battle with two sets of 
parents, has been extended indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weeks married Jeremy Weeks in February 1997. He obtained a  
restraining order June 1, saying his wife had been violent and he 
feared for his safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The order was in effect until June 14, but the couple reportedly  
wanted to resolve differences and try to win back their 
22-month-old son from state custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers with the state Department of Children &AMP; Families still  
are reviewing a case plan Mrs. Weeks signed -- which is the first 
step in getting her son back. 
</P>
<P>
	Weeks' attorney, Gary Fox, said the couple have not settled  
their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing's changed. They haven't reconciled,'' Fox said. ``As  
far as I know, he's going to file for divorce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his request for the order, Weeks, 21, said his wife was ``out  
of control'' and had hit and slapped him, waved knives, and been 
verbally abusive. The court order bars Mrs. Weeks, 20, from the 
couple's home and her husband's workplace and from the home of his 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weeks' life story was nationally reported when it was  
discovered in 1988 that she and another girl went home from a 
hospital with the wrong families. 
</P>
<P>
	After the other child, Arlena Twigg, died of heart disease, her  
family and Robert Mays, who had raised Weeks, battled over custody 
for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weeks' lawyer Diana Tennis said Mrs. Weeks wants the  
relationship with her husband to be as close as possible, and is 
committed to getting their son back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
