<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wohlers Headed to Minors Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Reliever Mark Wohlers is headed to the  
Cincinnati Reds' minor leagues again to see if he can throw strikes 
in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers threw batting practice to teammates again Saturday and  
did well enough to let the Reds approve his next step. He'll report 
to one of their minor league teams in the next week to start a 
rehabilitation assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready,'' Wohlers said. ``I'm excited with the way I'm  
throwing the ball. Now it's time to start applying what I've worked 
on over the last couple of months in game situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds got Wohlers from Atlanta in a trade for John Hudek on  
April 16 and put him on the disabled list with anxiety disorder. 
Essentially, he lost the ability to throw strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	After working out with pitching coach Don Gullett for two weeks,  
Wohlers was eager to start a rehabilitation assignment with 
Triple-A Indianapolis. It couldn't have gone much worse -- he walked 
five of the seven batters he faced and threw four wild pitches 
against Toledo on May 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he's been working out with Gullett and trying to fix  
flaws in his delivery by throwing batting practice to teammates. 
This time, he thinks he's ready to throw in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be good to get in there without the batting cage and  
with an umpire,'' he said. ``I never liked pitching batting 
practice anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gullett thinks Wohlers is ready, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's a matter of facing hitters and making the  
adjustments,'' Gullett said. ``I think he's a little tentative with 
his teammates in there. The real test is going to be against 
opposing hitters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds initially intended to send Wohlers to their rookie team  
in Sarasota, but later learned they couldn't do so. They weren't 
sure Saturday which team he would join. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds would like to start him in the lower minors and  
eventually move him up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel it's best to have him go against hitters at the lowest  
level and with the least amount of pressure before we start to 
elevate him,'' general manager Jim Bowden said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
