<HEADLINE> NYC's Safir May Pay for Oscar Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Police Commissioner Howard Safir has reportedly  
agreed to reimburse a Revlon executive $7,000 for an 
all-expenses-paid trip to the Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	A city investigation cleared Safir of any wrongdoing but  
recommended that he repay the money to avoid any hint of 
impropriety, the Daily News reported Friday, citing an unidentified 
source. 
</P>
<P>
	Safir came under fire after he and his wife flew to Los Angeles  
for the Oscars on March 21 aboard a corporate jet chartered by 
Revlon president and chief executive George Fellows. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani defended Safir, and the commissioner said  
he did not believe he broke any rules because Revlon does not do 
business with the city. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip came under more scrutiny after Safir initially said  
that because of a ``scheduling conflict,'' he would miss a City 
Council hearing about the police shooting of an unarmed African 
immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
	After being spotted on TV walking down the red carpet at the  
Oscars ceremony -- near actress Helen Hunt -- Safir took a red-eye 
flight back to New York and testified at the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Safir's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, had no comment Friday on  
whether he would reimburse Fellows. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
