<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Louisiana GOP Wants First Caucus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) -- Louisiana's Republican leaders decided  
today to hold a 2000 presidential caucus one week ahead of Iowa's 
traditional first-in-the-nation caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	But the question of whether the Republican National Committee  
would recognize the caucus was not addressed by the 160 Republicans 
who gathered for the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the members of the Louisiana GOP spent much of the time  
arguing over and eventually rejecting a competing proposal for 
Louisiana to hold the country's first-ever presidential primary 
with Internet voting. 
</P>
<P>
	It was defeated after dozens of Internet-balloting supporters  
walked out in a protest. They said they would file a lawsuit to 
reverse the caucus vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Benham, assistant executive director of the state party,  
had said Friday that the Republican National Committee wants all 
delegates selected on or after Feb. 7 -- the tentative date for 
Iowa's caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal for the Louisiana caucus did not specify a date but  
said it would be held a week before Iowa's caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Louisiana held a caucus before Iowa's caucus, but most  
candidates shunned Louisiana because they worried about offending 
Iowa Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidate Gary Bauer, former head of the Family Research  
Council, predicted the RNC will recognize the Louisiana caucus. He 
said party officials would work out problems, and that candidates 
would have enough time to campaign in both states. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think that's a decent enough interval that it won't  
cause too many problems,'' he said. ``I was just in Iowa the other 
day and folks seemed comfortable with the role Louisiana has 
taken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Francis, Louisiana's Republican Party chairman, said seven  
candidates have indicated they would participate in a Louisiana 
caucus in 2000. The only candidates he named were New Hampshire 
Sen. Bob Smith, Bauer and publisher Steve Forbes. Conservative 
columnist Pat Buchanan has already announced he would participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign officials for the man considered by many to be the  
front-runner for the Republican nomination, Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush, could not immediately be reached for comment on the Louisiana 
caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Louisiana event is being called a caucus, it will  
function much like a primary. Registered Republicans will cast 
ballots at 100 voting stations in the state's 64 parishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Polling places will be open for eight hours. In 1996, they were  
open only four hours -- a situation that created long lines. And the 
caucus was also criticized for low turnout. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20,000 Louisiana Republicans voted at 42 precincts in  
1996. In contrast, Iowa's caucus drew about 100,000 voters to 2,000 
sites 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
