<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toys R Us Makes Improvements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While shoddy customer service is a problem at  
many businesses, Toys R Us has been cited as one of the worst. 
</P>
<P>
	In an acknowledgment of its troubles, the Paramus, N.J.-based  
company plans to launch its biggest customer service overhaul ever 
Sunday. The initiative is intended to rally Toys R Us' 52,000 U.S. 
employees to change how they treat customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can lose a customer very fast, but you can win them back  
and part of that comes with great service,'' says Toys R Us chief 
executive Robert Nakasone. ``It doesn't cost any more to smile or 
be polite to a customer, and there's a huge payoff if they come 
back to the store again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a tough few years for Toys R Us, and its problems --  
including sluggish sales and profits -- have been linked in part to 
poor service. Shoppers complain of cramped aisles, confusing 
layouts and apathetic salespeople who seem unable to distinguish 
Barbie dolls from baseball bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate shopping at a store where the sales help literally  
barks at you if you have a question or need help finding 
something,'' says Jenny Wong, a New York mother of two who thinks 
of Toys R Us when asked about stores she really detests. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart dethroned Toys R Us as the nation's biggest retailer in  
1998. Wal-Mart and other discount chains are stealing away 
customers by selling toys for less and doing it with friendlier and 
more attentive service. 
</P>
<P>
	``Toys R Us allowed its stores to get tired, it allowed its  
service to get tired and that can't happen in any kind of 
retailing, but especially toy retailing,'' says Leonard Barry, a 
professor of retailing at Texas A&AMP;M University and author of 
``Discovering the Soul of Service.'' ``Toy stores are supposed to 
be a happy experience and selling today to the customer should be 
fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the last year, Toys R Us has started a major renovation of  
its 1,500 stores, developing a brighter, easier-to-navigate layout. 
The company has also added more products that kids today want, such 
as electronics, science and learning toys and beauty accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us is also stepping up its presence on the Internet, and  
later this month, is expected to unveil a new Web site that is 
easier to use. 
</P>
<P>
	But many analysts say the most crucial step in winning shoppers  
back is improving customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday night, every Toys R Us employee in the country will  
participate in a three-hour presentation and cheerleading session. 
The program will highlight the importance of courtesy and 
approaching the customer before the customer asks for help. 
</P>
<P>
	In the coming year, workers who never before got specialized  
training will be assigned a section of the store and taught about 
the toys there. 
</P>
<P>
	The program was designed with the help of the Disney Institute,  
which teaches corporations how to emulate the Magic Kingdom's 
customer service success. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Wong says the new program may prompt her to give Toys R Us  
another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's see what happens next Christmas,'' she says. ``If they  
are nice then, I'll admit the program is working.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 11:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
