<HEADLINE> Grant Finds Star Status 'Traumatic' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After taking nearly three years off, Hugh Grant  
is back with two romantic comedies -- and still complaining about 
the stress of being a movie star. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone came up to me today and said, `Hugh, a law has just  
been passed that you can't act anymore,' I'd be cracking open the 
champagne,'' Grant says in the July issue of US magazine. ``The 
older I get, the more traumatic I find it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant costars in ``Notting Hill'' opposite Julia Roberts and in  
the upcoming ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' with Jeanne Tripplehorn. He's 
also helping produce films with longtime girlfriend Elizabeth 
Hurley. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their dignified British demeanors, Hurley says the  
couple is a fiery match. 
</P>
<P>
	``We both have lightning mood swings and within seconds go from  
shrieking and yelling and throwing things to laughing hysterically 
and sitting on each other's lap,'' Hurley said. 
  	   	
</P>
