<DOCNO> APW19990612.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bush Makes Campaign Light-Hearted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                               *and    	
</P>
<P>
                            *MIKE GLOVER   	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writers    	
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In the first minute of his first  
campaign trip, George W. Bush grabbed the microphone aboard his 
``Great Expectations'' campaign plane and did his best imitation of 
a steward. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is your candidate, George W. Bush. Welcome aboard the  
inaugural flight of Great Expectations,'' he said, drawing polite 
laughter from his audience: Nearly 100 reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please store your expectations securely in your overhead bins,  
as they may shift during the trip and may fall and hurt someone -- 
especially me,'' Bush continued, reading from notes prepared by his 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a lighthearted way for the Texas governor to say, Give me  
a break. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading in polls, money raising and endorsements, Bush knows  
there is little chance that he can meet the expectations set for 
his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ask for your indulgence and seek your personal  
understanding that while you are traveling with a well-trained 
crew, for many of us this is our first solo flight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The son of former President George Bush was referring to himself  
and his staff, not the flight crew. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The day went rather smoothly for Bush, with little turbulence.  
</P>
<P>
	He did, however, nearly trip up -- coming close to showing a lack  
of knowledge about Iowa mainstays when he visited a charity 
clothing center in Cedar Rapids. 
</P>
<P>
	Squinting at a sign on the wall, Bush read it out loud: ``This  
is my Yon ... Younkers?'' He looked at a local resident for help. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a retail outlet here, sir,'' a woman told him. A rather  
well-known one. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	His blue dress shirt soaked through with sweat, Bush spotted a  
baby in a crowd of 2,000 at one of his speeches. 
</P>
<P>
	``OK,'' he said, realizing it was time for the typical campaign  
photo. ``Here we go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He gently took the 10-month old, Aaron Worf, from his mother and  
turned toward photographers. The doe-eyed baby didn't mind at first 
but suddenly broke into tears. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush teased one of the photographers. ``He took one look at  
you'' and cried, the governor said with a smile. ``It couldn't have 
been me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The photographer said he would take responsibility. ``This is  
the responsibility era,'' Bush said, using one of his campaign 
slogans to get another laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's mother, Donna, said she was impressed nonetheless.  
</P>
<P>
	``The man has charisma,'' he said. ``He makes people want to  
work for him and vote for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, meanwhile, was clearly getting the most  
attention of the GOP presidential rivals who showed up at the World 
Pork Expo on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	After she delivered her speech and headed to a nearby tent for a  
news conference and autograph session about half the crowd of 400 
left with her, not good news for the contenders who followed her to 
the podium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not comparing, I'm not looking at, I'm not being  
distracted by anything that other candidates are doing, even Lamar 
Alexander speaking as I'm speaking right now,'' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other rivals shrugged it off, including Ohio Rep. John Kasich.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said he's used to talking to an empty house -- he's a  
congressman,'' quipped one event organizer. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in Iowa can get a bit chummy, as Mrs. Dole already  
knows and Bush will surely learn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor and former Cabinet secretary both scheduled  
stops in Des Moines and in Cedar Rapids at different times of the 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	The two intersected briefly at the Cedar Rapids airport, where  
their respective campaign airplanes were parked next to each other 
on the tarmac. Mrs. Dole showed up to fly to California but took 
time to chat with some Bush aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Ari Fleischer, an aide to Mrs. Dole, was seen giving a big hug  
to Mindy Tucker, his counterpart with Bush. Bush was in a holding 
room in a nearby hangar during the encounter and the two candidates 
didn't meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker said Bush had planned to say hello to Mrs. Dole. ``I wish  
it would have happened,''' Fliescher said. ``It would have been a 
wonderful moment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 13:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms spread from the southern Plains into the Ohio  
Valley and across the Gulf Coast states on Saturday, with locally 
heavy rain falling in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms rolled across Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas during the  
morning, 
</P>
<P>
	Radar estimates of rainfall ranged up to 3 inches in parts of  
north-central Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	During the afternoon, thunderstorms also developed across much  
of eastern Texas and across wide sections of Louisiana, Arkansas, 
Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia and Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy storms were reported around New Orleans and from northern  
Mississippi into central Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther north, showers and scattered thunderstorms extended from  
Missouri and the southeast corner of Iowa across Illinois into 
parts of Wisconsin, Michigan, Indiana, Ohio and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Severe thunderstorm warnings were posted for sections of Ohio,  
Indiana, southeastern Michigan and central Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, scattered showers and storms also spread across  
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few light showers developed over eastern Montana  
and along the coast of northern California and southern Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	Isolated showers were possible over the Dakotas and northern  
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 29 at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to an early 
afternoon reading of 88 at Blythe, Calif. The lowest wind chill was 
22 at Jackson, Wyo., and the highest heat index by early afternoon 
was 96 at Del Rio, Texas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
