<DOCNO> APW19990612.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Ex-Boxer $10.7M in Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The actual fight lasted just 70 seconds.  
The legal battle took several years. And Randall ``Tex'' Cobb won a 
$10.7 million purse. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury on Friday ordered Time Inc. to pay $10.7 million to  
ex-heavyweight boxer for a 1993 Sports Illustrated article that 
said he fixed a fight and shared cocaine with the loser. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' attorney George Bochetto said. 
``This jury set this man free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, 46, said the story headlined ``The Fix Was In'' ended his  
boxing career and nearly sidelined his acting pursuits. The jury 
deliberated about four hours before awarding him $2.2 million in 
punitive damages on top of the $8.5 million in compensatory damages 
it awarded Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The article described the 1992 bout between Cobb and Sonny  
Barch, a journeyman fighter and former Memphis State football 
player. The magazine said Cobb and Barch discussed how to throw the 
fight, with Cobb complaining of an injured shoulder and hoping to 
end the match quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Barch said he told Cobb: ``I'm going to have to  
hit you to make it look good. But I won't hit your shoulder.'' 
Barch said that Cobb responded: ``Bubba, I appreciate it. I'll make 
it up to you,'' according to the article. 
</P>
<P>
	Barch allowed Cobb to hit him three times, dropping to a knee  
each time and triggering the three-knockdown rule, Sports 
Illustrated reported. Cobb was declared the winner by technical 
knockout 70 seconds into the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine also reported that Barch said he, Cobb and a fight  
promoter shared cocaine after the bout. Sports Illustrated reported 
that both Barch and Cobb had flunked post-fight drug tests and the 
fight was declared a no-contest. In a follow-up, Sports Illustrated 
said that Cobb had tested positive for marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Juror Steve Reynolds, a Nashville schoolteacher, said the story  
was unfair, slanted and ``based on a shady individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Robinson, managing editor of CNN-SI and a former Sports  
Illustrated senior editor who worked on the story, said the verdict 
``shocked us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our position is the story is accurate. The jury findings are  
not supported by the evidence,'' he said. ``We're very confident we 
will prevail on appeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, a former Nashville resident who now lives in Philadelphia,  
has had roles in several movies, including ``Liar, Liar,'' 
``Raising Arizona,'' ``Uncommon Valor'' and ``The Golden Child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $2.2 million in punitive damages is approximately how much  
Sports Illustrated made in net income per issue last year, 
according to testimony. Sports Illustrated, a subsidiary of Time 
Inc., published 52 issues last year and reported earnings of more 
than $112 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Disclose Financial Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators are not only legislating the future  
of cyberspace, they're also investing their personal money in such 
lucrative high-tech companies as America Online and Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen senators reported buying or holding stock in  
high-tech companies in amounts ranging from as little as $1,000 to 
as much as $1 million, according to disclosure reports released 
Friday that detailed their personal finances in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The forms provide a glimpse into the assets, liabilities and  
outside earnings of senators -- many of whom are millionaires -- but 
describe figures in broad ranges. House members will release their 
forms next Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports are just another sign of how much Internet companies  
have become a powerful force in both political and financial 
circles, experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The high-tech industry has been the golden boy of the last  
session of Congress,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of 
the Center for Responsive Politics, which studies political 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their batting average is as high, if not higher, than any  
other industry in Washington. Everyone is pursuing their money in 
campaign contributions and everyone is trying to attach themselves 
to what they see is a rising star,'' Makinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress passed several bills favorable to the industry last  
year, including a temporary ban on Internet taxes, fewer limits on 
hiring immigrants with computer skills, new copyright protections 
and $100 million for the next generation of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., boasted a diverse portfolio in  
high-tech stocks -- reporting investments of between $100,001 and 
$250,000 in Microsoft, $100,001-$250,000 in Intel and other large 
stakes in Sun, Cisco Systems, IBM, Dell and Network Associates Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``The senator doesn't feel any conflict of interest with any of  
his financial holdings. His voting record is totally divorced from 
any of his financial holdings,'' said Gary Hoitsma, Inhofe's 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., and his wife reported shares in Intel,  
Microsoft and Lucent Technologies worth between $250,000 and 
$600,000. Graham also reported owning stock in Sun Microsystems, 
Inc., MCI WorldCom Inc. and Motorola. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., who didn't vote in 1998,  
owns $500,001 to $1 million in IBM stock and $250,000-$500,000 each 
in Intuit, Motorola and Cisco Systems, which makes the equipment 
that makes up the backbone of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller Internet investors included Sens. Tim Hutchinson,  
R-Ark., and Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska. Hutchinson purchased shares 
last December in America Online, Lucent and Ticketmaster Online. 
Murkowski owned $15,001 to $50,000 in Lucent stock along with 
shares in Sun, Motorola and Iomega. 
</P>
<P>
	Some senators reported their greatest wealth came from spouses.  
</P>
<P>
	Teresa Heinz, the wife of Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., is an heir  
to the H.J. Heinz food fortune through her late husband, former 
Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa. Her wealth has been estimated in the 
hundreds of millions of dollars, with investments that include more 
than $1 million in both Intel and Nokia and $500,001 to $1 million 
in Sun, according to Kerry's filing. 
</P>
<P>
	Another senator with a wealthy spouse was Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.,  
whose wife, Anne, reported making more than $1 million from the 
sale of stock options for Quest Communications, a cellular phone 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial disclosure reports also provided some atypical  
investments: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., received framed ship's papers  
signed by President James Madison and Secretary of State Robert 
Smith worth $2,500 from the Conservative Political Action 
Committee. McConnell deemed it acceptable under the Senate gifts 
rule because it was presented in recognition of his public service 
work on behalf of the First Amendment to the Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sen Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., received a painting, worth $6,824,  
from the Vietnam Veterans of America Foundation to celebrate the 
establishment of the Patrick J. Leahy Humanitarian Award 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sen. Jim Bunning, R-Ky., who pitched a perfect baseball game  
in 1964 for the Philadelphia Phillies, earned $34,884 from baseball 
card shows and other memorabilia activities. Bunning, inducted into 
the Hall of Fame in 1996, received a waiver to accept a free trip 
to Cooperstown, N.Y., for last July's ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the oldest member of the Senate  
at 96, valued four burial plots in Aiken, S.C., at between $1,001 
and $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., earned $29,286 in residuals from  
his work as a movie actor -- his credits include ``Hunt for Red 
October'' and ``Die Hard 2'' -- before entering politics. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 15:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ALS-Stricken Catfish Hunter Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter's arms dangled  
limply by his side. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't raise them to acknowledge the emotional ovation from  
the crowd, his old teammates, his family and the ballplayers there 
to honor him and play the game Hunter handled with such passion and 
skill during a 15-year Hall of Fame pitching career. 
</P>
<P>
	His 3-year-old grandson, Taylor, did it for him, waving his  
hands to the crowd as he, Hunter and his wife, Helen, circled the 
field in a 1965 Mustang convertible before Saturday's game between 
the Oakland Athletics and Los Angeles Dodgers. It was a day to 
recognize Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, who is battling amyotrophic 
lateral sclerosis, commonly known as Lou Gehrig's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like only 10 years ago I was out here pitching,  
giving up all those home runs,'' said Hunter, back in Oakland to 
raise money to fight ALS. It was his first trip back since the A's 
retired his No. 27 in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The illness progressively destroys nerves controlling muscle  
movement and eventually can lead to paralysis and death. 
</P>
<P>
	It's responsible for withering Hunter's arms, including the  
golden right arm that helped him win 224 games, including a perfect 
game, and five World Series rings while playing for the Kansas City 
and Oakland Athletics and the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	As his grandfather stood behind him on the mound where he had  
pitched so well, Taylor threw out the ceremonial first pitch. There 
to catch it was Jim Pagliaroni, who caught Hunter's perfect game 
against Minnesota in Oakland on May 8, 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	``This day is a tribute to you and your ability to overcome any  
obstacle,'' former A's broadcaster Monte Moore said in an 
introduction that brought a roar from the crowd. ``Today is 
dedicated to your vision of living with ALS and your pursuit of a 
cure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pagliaroni was joined by other former A's teammates of Hunter  
who were part of a dynasty that won three straight World Series 
from 1972-74. They included Joe Rudi, Ray Fosse, Dick Green, John 
``Blue Moon'' Odom, Vida Blue, Rick Monday, Campy Campaneris and 
Reggie Jackson, who greeted Hunter with a kiss on the cheek during 
a news conference before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a small way to say, `I'm your friend,''' Jackson  
said. ``There was nothing more important for me than to be here 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the most respected player really I've ever been around.  
That's why you see all these players here in unison. We admired him 
for the way he carried himself and the person that he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter was overwhelmed by the show of support and his voice  
cracked more than once. Near the end of the news conference, he was 
asked where he was in his fight with ALS and how he was doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is, ALS, there's no cure for it and I know  
that,'' Hunter said. ``God can cure it and that's the only way we 
can go. We can turn to doctors. We can turn to anything you want. 
But God's the only thing you can turn to, and your family and 
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to live with it,'' Hunter added. ``You've got to  
keep on going. You can't stop. I'm not going to stop. That's the 
reason I'm out here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter's foundation, which received a $20,000 check from the A's  
before the game, is dedicated to increasing awareness of ALS and 
funding research grants. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter said he's staying positive and giving his fight against  
ALS everything he has. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a saying in my locker when I was at Kansas City my  
first year,'' Hunter told the crowd. ``It said, `Winning isn't 
everything but wanting to is.' If you want to do something bad 
enough, you've got to work for it. That's what I'm going to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
