<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Hall of Fame Turns 60 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Every time Phil Niekro returns to  
Cooperstown, he makes a beeline for the Baseball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love coming back here, especially when your plaque's hanging  
on the wall,'' the former Atlanta Braves knuckleballer said. ``And 
it's still there. I keep checking. You can't help not to. When you 
walk in, you're going to go see if it's still there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Niekro returned to Cooperstown again on Saturday, but his plaque  
was an afterthought. The Hall of Fame was marking its 60th 
anniversary, and Niekro was one of the guests of honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a mystique about this town that I've never felt in any  
other little town I've ever been to,'' Niekro said. ``It's a family 
town. It's super-friendly. It's got the lake, it's got the hills, 
it's got the fresh air. It's got everything you want in a little 
town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And on this day it had a good old-fashioned parade, with Niekro,  
former Baltimore third baseman Brooks Robinson, and longtime 
Philadelphia Phillie Robin Roberts leading the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a great parade!'' Niekro said. ``The boys and girls and  
the grandmas and grandpas and the balloons, the bands. That was 
probably as good a parade as I've ever been in. There was a smile 
on every face. Every hand was waving. It was like you wanted to go 
sit on the curb and watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty years ago, about 15,000 people, most of them from in and  
around Cooperstown, attended the opening ceremonies of the Hall of 
Fame. On Saturday, a crowd of about 4,000 lined Main Street for the 
festivities. If only Ernie Banks were here -- the day was 
picture-perfect, fit to play two. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big thrill to be here,'' Robinson said. ``The guys  
should come back. I wouldn't miss it. It's part of a tradition. 
It's the greatest hall of fame there is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The day also carried its share of nostalgia, especially for the  
small group of people known as the 39ers -- those who were here June 
12, 1939 when the doors to the Hall opened for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't sadness,'' recalled Catherine Walker, who was 8  
years old then and now works at the Hall of Fame as attendance 
supervisor. ``Just memories that have gone by. This is a special 
day. Who would have thought way back then as an 8-year-old that I 
would be riding in this parade?'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's unlikely that any of the first five members -- Babe Ruth, Ty  
Cobb, Honus Wagner, Christy Mathewson, and Walter Johnson -- would 
recognize the place today. From its humble beginnings in a 
1,200-square-foot building, the Hall of Fame has undergone five 
expansions that have transformed it into a 60,000-square-foot mecca 
for baseball junkies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really something to think of that small building and what  
it's grown into,'' said Homer Osterhoudt, who as a 19-year-old 
worked on the construction of the three-story brick museum. ``This 
is a special day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And it was special in 1939, so much so that Ruth came out of  
retirement to play in an all-star game that also included the likes 
of Wagner, Eddie Collins, Charlie Gehringer, Dizzy Dean and Mel 
Ott. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the Hall's attraction is its exclusivity -- only 181 of  
the more than 15,000 men who have played the game at its highest 
levels are enshrined. But getting in didn't occupy a lot of 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	't think any of us ever started out thinking we were going to be  
Hall of Famers,'' Robinson said. ``I certainly knew what it was all 
about. I knew the history of the game and what it represented. To 
be a part of it is absolutely wonderful. It's like your own little 
fraternity.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
