<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Pacers Face Many Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- This was to be the year the Indiana Pacers  
took the next step, winning their first NBA championship since 
entering the league in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the aging team once again began its summer vacation in  
late spring amid questions about whether coach Larry Bird will 
stick around. 
</P>
<P>
	A 90-82 victory Friday by the New York Knicks sent the Pacers  
home pondering their futures after being ousted in the conference 
finals for the fourth time in six years. 
</P>
<P>
	The same problems that frustrated Indiana during the  
lockout-shortened season haunted the Pacers against the younger, 
smaller, quicker and more athletic Knicks. Inability to hold big 
leads and win close games in the final minutes proved fatal. 
</P>
<P>
	Club president Donnie Walsh now has a major challenge to prepare  
the team for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight players are 30 or older, including all five starters, and  
they're all under contract for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, there's uncertainty if the competitive spirit that  
put Bird in the Hall of Fame as a player will allow him to overcome 
the disappointments of 1999 and return as coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very disappointed with the way we played in this  
series,'' said Bird. He has one more year on his contract as coach 
and has said he won't make any decision on his future until meeting 
with his players. 
</P>
<P>
	That meeting will take place sometime next week, when it is  
expected that the players will tell Bird they want him back. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana's only consolation was a Central Division championship.  
</P>
<P>
	But Indiana lost two of its three games at home against New York  
after sweeping Milwaukee and Philadelphia in the first two rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The only fingerpointing after the team's last loss was by Reggie  
Miller, who had a history for dramatic success in the playoffs, 
particularly against New York. He pointed at himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Horrendous. Horrendous,'' Miller said of his 3-for-18 shooting  
effort on Friday. ``A lot of open looks. They were looking to ride 
my back this round, and I didn't do it for them. So I have to take 
responsibility for that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed because I definitely feel like I let our  
franchise down -- really our state. For me to come up so short in 
such a crucial part and a crucial time, it's very difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird spread the blame around.  
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like we always had three guys who played well in  
each game. We never did get the five guys that we needed to win the 
ball game,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Pacers pushed eventual champion Michael Jordan  
and Chicago to seven games last year before falling in the final 
minutes of the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be changes,'' Antonio Davis said Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``What changes will be made I don't know. But we've asked  
management time and time again to give us chances and they've given 
us chances and kept the team together and everybody feels like we 
let them down. So anything that they do I'm sure we're going to 
agree with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers began preparing for the season long before their  
union and management reached an agreement to end the lockout that 
threatened the season. Starting in October, nearly every player 
participated in voluntary workouts on an almost daily basis in 
anticipation it would pay off. 
</P>
<P>
	It did. At least for a while.  
</P>
<P>
	Indiana got off to its best start since joining the NBA, winning  
nine of its first 12 games. It finished the regular season with 
four consecutive victories, giving it a 33-17 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven straight playoff wins lifted Indiana's confidence.  
</P>
<P>
	Then came the Knicks, the first eighth-seeded team to reach the  
conference finals. New York ended Indiana's streak of 12 straight 
home playoff victories in Game 1, outscoring Indiana 11-3 in the 
final 2:09 for a 93-90 triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana held on to win Game 2 88-86 after the Knicks managed to  
overcome a 17-point first-half deficit to lead 78-72 in the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	New York regained the advantage in Game 3 on Larry Johnson's l  
four-point play at the buzzer. Indiana again tied the series in 
Game 4, then returned home to lose Game 5 after building a 28-14 
lead in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough, very tough,'' Mark Jackson said. ``All the work,  
all the effort, all the energy. Tough.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
