<DOCNO> APW19990612.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 07:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Testing Campaign Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush, the untested  
presidential front-runner, plunged into the 2000 campaign today by 
defending his ``compassionate conservative'' brand of politics as 
he hoped to rise to the high expectations set for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who leads in presidential polling despite not spending a  
single day on the campaign trail, began a four-day trip to the 
presidential proving grounds of Iowa and New Hampshire by boarding 
his aptly named ``Great Expectations'' campaign plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ready to go?'' Bush asked his press secretary. It is a  
question that will be asked about the Texas governor again and 
again in the coming weeks: Is Bush ready to go? 
</P>
<P>
	Bush joked about the expectations with reporters on his plane.  
Pretending he was the pilot, Bush seized a microphone and 
announced, ``Please store your expectations securely in the 
overhead bins, as they might shift during the trip and may fall and 
hurt someone -- especially me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor's speech today, the first major address of  
his 2000 Republican bid, traced the broad themes of the campaign 
without offering specific policies, according to advisers with 
access to drafts. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush argued that Republicans can be conservative -- cut taxes,  
trim welfare rolls, reduce crime, improve schools, demand and 
promote personal responsibility -- without being mean about it. He 
vowed not to retreat from criticism, saying he has chosen the 
ground of ``compassionate conservatism'' and will not waver from 
that spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he makes his first public campaign appearances today,  
Bush launched his White House bid with private fund-raising events 
Friday in St. Louis and Chicago. ``See you in Iowa,'' he told 
reporters afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have joined with GOP presidential rivals to call  
``compassionate conservatism'' poll-driven political jargon. Former 
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander accused Bush of using ``weasel 
words.'' Former Vice President Dan Quayle prohibited his staff from 
using them. 
</P>
<P>
	There might be a tinge of jealousy behind the criticism. Bush  
built a huge lead in polls while remaining in Austin, sheltered 
from the perils of campaigning as his foes traipsed across the 
country for months. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio and former American Red  
Cross president Elizabeth Dole were campaigning in Iowa today, 
ceding no ground to Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, a distant second behind Bush in polling, unveiled a  
10-point farm plan and dispatched aides to tell reporters that she 
was offering specific proposals while the front-runner sticks to 
generalities. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich offered reporters a hamburger lunch if they travel with  
him Sunday, knowing few would accept. It was a lighthearted jab at 
Bush, who was holding a lobster bake for the more than 100 
journalists flying to Maine and New Hampshire to witness his coming 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, alarmed by polls showing Bush ahead of Vice President  
Al Gore, are linking the Texas governor to an unpopular Congress. 
More than half of House Republicans have endorsed the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can't influence them now, how will you do it as  
president?''' Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic 
National Committee, asked rhetorically. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush shrugged off the criticism.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a tempting target to say George W. is a person  
who hasn't had to fight for anything in his life,'' he said in an 
interview before the trip. ``But I know what I believe in and I 
know the battles I've been through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, 52, is many ways the phantom front-runner. Though far  
ahead of the pack in polling, money-raising and endorsements, the 
son of former President George Bush is little-known outside Texas. 
He is also untested as a national candidate, anointed the GOP 
favorite without a single campaign appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	His success is due in part to his name. One recent poll found  
that when questioners distinguished between Bush and his father, 
the governor's ratings dropped 15 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush secured re-election in 1998 with nearly 70 percent of the  
vote, including large portions of female and minority voters who 
traditionally shy away from the GOP. Though the Texas governorship 
is given little constitutional power, Bush can take credit for 
higher school scores, less crime, fewer welfare cases and lower 
taxes in the nation's second largest state. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's blend of conservative politics couched in soothing,  
moderate rhetoric could help move the GOP to the center -- much as 
President Clinton refocused his party away from its liberal 
extremes in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	His critics say Bush is poll-driven, ideologically shallow and a  
natural-born waffler. Bush fostered the criticism by giving vague 
or conflicting opinions on national issues while overseeing the 
state's legislative session this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In Iowa, Bush planned to visit a charity to highlight his  
efforts in Texas to get faith-based organizations involved in 
solving social problems, a pet issue of conservatives that Gore 
embraced recently. He hopes to stake his claim to the issue without 
mentioning the vice president. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
