<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Norman Richardson    	
</P>
<P>
	SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) -- Norman Richardson, state editor of The  
Times from 1957 to 1974 and later executive editor of the Temple 
(Texas) Daily Telegram, died Friday from kidney failure. He was 64. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was born in Ruston and graduated from Louisiana Tech  
University. 
</P>
<P>
	His reporting on hurricanes that struck the Louisiana and Texas  
coasts in the 1960s won several awards from The Associated Press, 
including the 1969 Frank C. Allen Award and a 1965 AP Managing 
Editor's Association award. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson retired from news in 1979.  
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by a daughter and three grandchildren.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Sabra Dalby Rightmire    	
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Sabra Dalby Rightmire, who worked to teach others  
about a rare form of skin cancer after she became ill, died 
Wednesday from complications of the disease. She was 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Rightmire was diagnosed July 30, 1998 with the metastatic  
melanoma, a form of skin cancer that attacks the body's organs and 
usually causes death within months. 
</P>
<P>
	She became a vocal member of an on-line support group for  
melanoma patients and caregivers. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1989 graduate of University Liggett School, Mrs. Rightmire  
graduated from Wellesley College and was pursuing a master's degree 
at New York University at the time of her death. 
</P>
<P>
	Her survivors include her husband, Eric; parents Ronald and Ann  
Dalby; her sister, a brother Brian; a grandmother, and nieces and 
nephews. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
