<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Deny News Has Influence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- On his way to Heritage High School a few  
hours after a 15-year-old student wounded six classmates, Rockdale 
District Attorney Richard Read saw tearful students clinging to 
each other in shock. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, he faced cameras and microphones as the news  
media covered the nation's latest school shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Read says it was not the news coverage that cemented his  
decision to seek permission to try the juvenile suspect in the May 
20 shooting as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who makes a decision like this in a vacuum is acting  
irresponsibly,'' says Read. ``But to put it simply, this kid walked 
into a school, opened fire, and by doing that, robbed a community 
of its sense of security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As public attention focuses on the recent rash of school  
shootings, prosecutors say they don't pander to the media or voters 
when they decide to move high-profile juvenile cases to adult 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	But some child advocates disagree, arguing that lawmakers and  
prosecutors are sacrificing the future of many savable children in 
an effort to appear tough on crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have given the prosecutors absolute discretion,  
you've skewed the system,'' says Helen Leiner, chair of the 
juvenile justice committee of the National Association of Criminal 
Defense Lawyers. ``High-profile cases result in high-profile 
responses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Conyers case, Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon faces 21 charges  
including aggravated assault, cruelty to children and weapons 
violations and a potential sentence of 351 years in prison if 
convicted. If a judge decides to keep the case in juvenile court, 
Solomon's maximum sentence would be 60 months in the youth system. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Justice Department, 40 states and the District  
of Columbia passed laws in 1992-1995 making it easier for juveniles 
to be tried as adults. Thirty-eight of the states expanded laws 
covering crimes that automatically require adult treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a positive trend, if you ask me,'' said James  
Backstrom, the Dakota County Attorney in Hastings, Minn., and 
co-chair of the National District Attorneys Association's juvenile 
justice advisory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Georgia strengthened rules against juveniles charged  
with what prosecutors call the ``seven deadly sins'' -- murder, 
voluntary manslaughter, armed robbery, rape, aggravated sexual 
battery, aggravated sodomy and aggravated child molestation. Anyone 
over 13 who is charged with one of these crimes is automatically 
tried in adult court. 
</P>
<P>
	Any other cases -- except for defendants 15 or older involving a  
charge with a possible life sentence -- require prosecutors to 
petition the juvenile court to have the case moved. Read has begun 
that process in Solomon's case; the court is awaiting the results 
of psychological exams before holding a hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, the number of juvenile cases moved to adult court is  
up to 1 percent in 1996 from less than 0.6 percent in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Leiner says the system is unfair to many children, citing  
the case of a mentally disabled 15-year-old in Florida who was put 
in an adult jail -- his family couldn't afford the $500 bail -- and 
faced a life sentence for stealing $2 in lunch money. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida prosecutors have the discretion to take any juvenile  
case to adult court involving a violent felony. However, the 
charges against Anthony Laster were dropped after the lead witness 
changed his testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	In a high-profile Georgia case, 15-year-old Jonathan Miller was  
tried as adult after a fatal attack on a 13-year-old neighbor. 
Miller, who hit the boy in the back of the head and then kicked 
him, was convicted of murder and assault and sentenced to life in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue Ridge Circuit District Attorney Garry Moss said media  
attention surrounding Miller's case had nothing to do with his 
decision to bring charges that automatically moved the case to 
adult court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an elective office and should be political,'' Moss  
added. ``We are the public's most accessible office when it comes 
to law enforcement, but it's still our responsibility to do the law 
right first, and then worry about the public.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
