<HEADLINE> Maryland Commuter Train Kills Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANDY HOOK, Md. (AP) -- Two men waiting for friends after a day  
of tubing on the Potomoc River were killed when they were struck by 
a passenger train, Maryland State Police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Bricken, 20, and Michael Caputo, 21, died instantly  
Friday evening after being hit by the Maryland Commuter Rail 
Service train, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The train was carrying about 50 people and was traveling at  
about 50 mph. Passengers were loaded onto another train. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Lu Herman, spokeswoman for the state police, said the  
victims were waiting for two people who had gone to fetch their 
car. She said the engineer did not see them. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men were sitting on inner tubes at the edge of the  
tracks as the train neared, said Rebekah White, who was near the 
scene with members of her family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then the first gentleman was cartwheeling through the air,  
arms and legs going everywhere, and the other gentleman was like a 
top spinning around on the road,'' said her husband, Rocky White. 
</P>
<P>
	The witnesses rushed over to check for signs of life, but both  
men were dead. 
  	   	
</P>
