<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lobo To Miss WNBA Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rebecca Lobo, the New York Liberty's leading  
rebounder the past two years, will have to watch her teammates 
rebound for the remainder of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo's season lasted all of 42 seconds. It was ended by a torn  
anterior cruciate ligament in her left knee in the first minute of 
the Liberty's season opener against the Cleveland Rockers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm terribly disappointed that this happened,'' Lobo said  
Friday at Beth Israel Hospital, where she was undergoing therapy. 
``But I'm upbeat because I'm in great care. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will be on the sidelines during the season cheering on my  
teammates. I will be back next season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 Lobo, who led Connecticut to a 35-0 record and the  
NCAA championship in 1995, will be difficult to replace. 
</P>
<P>
	In the WNBA's first two seasons, she averaged 12.1 points and  
7.1 rebounds while playing in all 58 New York games. During the 
league's inaugural season in 1997, she was chosen to the All-WNBA 
second team. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge loss to our team,'' general manager Carol  
Blazejowski said. ``You don't replace a player of Rebecca's caliber 
overnight. The team, as a whole, will have to raise their level of 
play and fill the void that this injury creates to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty coach Richie Adubato, making his Liberty debut, was  
heartbroken. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rebecca is an integral part of both our team's offense and  
defense,'' he said. ``Losing her for the rest of the season is 
difficult. She was having a great training camp and playing very 
well. ... It now means that her teammates are going to have to step 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last four or five days, she was rebounding, knocking down  
jump shots, catching the ball in the low post and making her 
move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Teresa Weatherspoon: ``It's an awful feeling to know what  
Rebecca is going through. ... We will definitely pick it up for 
Rebecca.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sue Wicks, a member of the 1987 gold medal-winning U.S. team at  
the Pan American Games, will play additional minutes, as will 
rookies Tamika Whitmore and Michele VanGorp. 
</P>
<P>
	Team physician Dr. Susan Craig-Scott said Lobo will have surgery  
in 2-3 weeks. Craig-Scott said Lobo's rehabilitation will take a 
minimum of six months. 
</P>
<P>
	``She should be ready next season,'' the doctor said. ``We  
expect her to be back. She's a tough kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo was in tears Thursday night, especially when talking to her  
mother at the hospital and when speaking with her father by 
telephone. She was more upbeat Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope my New Year's Eve present will be that I will be back  
on the court,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was very upset when the injury first occurred, but she  
calmed down in the locker room.'' Craig-Scott said. ``She was in 
good spirits this morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo, the youngest member of the 1996 U.S. Olympic team that won  
the gold medal, said her worst injury before this season required 
arthroscopic knee surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never felt anything like this before,'' she said. ``It's the  
first injury that's taken me out of commission for this long a 
time. It's the first time I've had something of this magnitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo was hurt while grabbing a rebound after Kym Hampton's  
missed shot. She pivoted and fell, clutching her leg for about 30 
seconds as play continued before an official called an injury 
timeout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went in, got a sweet offensive rebound,'' Lobo said. ``And  
when I came down, I thought somebody hit me on the side of the 
knee, and it just buckled. ... But people who watched video of the 
play said nobody hit me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo was helped off the floor by Hampton and Wicks.  
</P>
<P>
	``She was crying,'' Wicks said. ``I didn't even ask her how she  
was, she just shook her head. She knew immediately that it was bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rebecca's so tough that she wouldn't stay on the ground with a  
twisted ankle or something small. I've never seen her cry, so you 
know it's bad.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
