<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Morningland Cheese Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Missouri producer is expanding its recall of  
cheese that may be contaminated with listeria, a potentially 
life-threatening bacterium. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningland Dairy Farms Inc. of Mountain View, Mo., stopped  
producing and distributing cheese last month after the Food and 
Drug Administration found the bacteria in another type of cheese 
that Morningland had already recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Friday, the company also recalled 228 pounds of Morningland  
Dairy Mild Cheddar Cheese that it had produced before the FDA 
action. The cheese is made from unpasteurized milk, and 
contamination showed up in health tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The mild cheddar cheese was sold in plastic bags ranging from  
one-half to 20 pounds, with the code C179 written in ink on the 
label. 
</P>
<P>
	Listeria can cause serious, potentially fatal, infections in  
young children, the elderly and people with weak immune systems and 
also can cause miscarriages. Healthy people, however, usually 
suffer short-term symptoms, including diarrhea, nausea, abdominal 
pain and fever. 
</P>
<P>
	No illnesses have been reported from the suspect cheese.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
