<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 13:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympians Urged To Press for Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Athletes should take the lead in pressing for  
reforms in the Olympics, a former congressional leader who authored 
a critical report of the Salt Lake bribery scandal said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said he was  
impressed by the path of changes the International Olympic 
Committee was pursuing in the wake of its worst corruption case and 
that ``there is a reasonable chance that something good will 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said that more time was needed to tell if the IOC's  
actions were long-term changes or ``tinkering at the edges in a 
manner that is deemed sufficient to get past this problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The course should be clear by year's end, Mitchell told a group  
of former Olympic athletes gathered to discuss their role in the 
reform process. He urged them to move to the front of the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Athletes must take the leadership role,'' Mitchell said in the  
keynote address before OATH, which was founded last March at the 
height of the scandal. ``You are in the best position of all to be 
influential because of the prestige your great performances and 
your record gives you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OATH, for Olympic Advocates Together Honorably, was co-founded  
by Canadian swimmer Mark Tewskbury and businessman George Marsland 
to work for ``systemic reform'' in the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	`The unassailability of the IOC has, unfortunately, become the  
unaccountability of the IOC,'' Marsland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell headed a five-member panel appointed by the U.S.  
Olympic Committee that investigated the Salt Lake scandal and 
concluded that the case resulted from ``an improper culture of 
gift-giving'' entrenched in the system for choosing Olympic host 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also said Olympic leaders, including IOC president  
Juan Antonio Samaranch, had ignored signs of corruption long before 
the scandal broke. 
</P>
<P>
	While the USOC quickly adopted the commission's recommendations  
of more openness and accountability, the IOC has moved more slowly, 
and Mitchell has been criticized by some Olympic leaders for trying 
to impose American ways on one of the world's most broadly based 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	As he did at a Senate Commerce Committee hearing in April,  
Mitchell said it was much easier for the USOC to quickly adopt 
reforms because the IOC had to do so much more. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we recommended to the USOC was to take two aspirin and go  
to bed,'' he said. ``What we recommended to the IOC was brain 
surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was why the focus must swing back to the stars of the  
games, Mitchell said, and why their participation was critical in 
assuring that the scandal of Salt Lake did not recur. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think most IOC members care much what I say,''  
Mitchell said at a luncheon attended by more than two dozen former 
Olympic competitors. ``I think the IOC will care very much what you 
say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a news conference, the former Senate leader and head  
of the panel that brokered peace in Northern Ireland said the 
athletes -- who have been among the loudest critics of the scandal -- 
must use personal persuasion to state their case. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no substitute for making a direct personal case on  
the merits,'' he said. ``And there is no one (than the athletes) 
with a higher standing with the public. They are in a unique 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Mitchell commission's recommendations that the IOC  
quickly adopted was agreeing to include athletes as members, with 
the ranks filled by direct election of their peers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell spent much of the lunch talking with Johan Olav Koss,  
an Olympic speedskating champion and vocal critic of IOC 
leadership, who said he was pleased with initial steps taken by IOC 
2000, the 80-member task force that will draw up reforms. Koss is 
an athlete representative on the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell said he was encouraged by Koss' comments.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is a process. I think it is open,'' he said. ``I  
think there is a reasonable chance that something good will 
happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
