<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Rallies Reform Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura, the Reform Party's  
only statewide officer holder, told party activists at the state 
convention today to work hard and be patient. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention was the first since Ventura's stunning victory  
last November, and attendance of more than 200 delegates doubled 
the turnout at the 1998 convention. Still, the party's future 
viability is far from secure. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has major party status, making it eligible for public  
subsidies. But to maintain that, the party's presidential or U.S. 
Senate candidate must receive at least 5 percent of the vote next 
year. No strong candidate has emerged for either office. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders are looking to the state's 201 legislative seats,  
which are all up for re-election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, the former professional wrestler and first Reform Party  
candidate in the nation to win a statewide election, told activists 
to send him company at the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't sit on our laurels of winning governor. We can't do  
that. Frankly, I'll tell you why: I'm lonesome,'' Ventura said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
