<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belle Returns to Orioles' Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Albert Belle, benched for one game after a  
shouting match with Baltimore manager Ray Miller, returned to the 
Orioles lineup for Saturday's game against the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle didn't play Friday night, breaking his streak of 392  
consecutive games played. He had taken over the longest active 
streak in the majors after teammate Cal Ripken voluntarily sat down 
late last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, who has been suspended six times during his troubled  
career, clashed with Miller after failing to run out a ninth-inning 
grounder during Wednesday's 4-2 victory at Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	In the bottom of the inning, Miller replaced Belle in the  
outfield with Rich Amaral, a move the manager said he planned to 
make anyway. But Belle was unaware of the change until he was on 
his way to the outfield. 
</P>
<P>
	After he jogged back to the dugout, TV cameras caught an  
exchange of profanities between Miller and Belle. The outfielder 
had to be restrained by teammate Jeff Reboulet. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller refused to say he was disciplining Belle by keeping him  
on the bench for Friday's game, which the Orioles won 6-2. Belle's 
replacement, Jeff Conine, went 3-for-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albert Belle got the day off. That was my choice,'' Miller  
said. ``Any other reflection or matters about that subject will be 
handled internally. Let's leave it that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, batting cleanup, was booed loudly by the Turner Field  
crowd when he came up in the first inning Saturday. He responded 
with a single to right and scored on Will Clark's two-run homer, 
giving the Orioles a 4-0 lead. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
