<DOCNO> APW19990612.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Deal Plesac to Arizona </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dan Plesac, having the worst season of his  
13-year career, was traded by the Toronto Blue Jays to the Arizona 
Diamondbacks on Saturday for shortstop Tony Batista and 
right-hander John Frascatore. 
</P>
<P>
	Plesac, 37, who ranks 25th in major league history with 788  
appearances, was 0-3 with an 8.34 ERA in 30 games for the Blue 
Jays. He allowed a run in one inning Friday against Philadelphia 
after entering Toronto's game against the Mets in the 14th inning 
Wednesday and giving up a game-winning single to Rey Ordonez. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander appeared in a career-high 78 games in 1998, his  
third consecutive season with 70 or more games. Plesac is 
153-for-216 in career save situations (.708). 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays announced the deal shortly before their game  
Saturday night against the Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Batista, 25, became Arizona's starting shortstop last season  
when Jay Bell moved to second base. However, Batista had lost the 
full-time starting job in recent weeks and had been platooned at 
the position with Andy Fox. Batista was batting .257 with five home 
runs and 21 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Batista was Arizona's 14th pick, and the 27th choice overall, in  
last year's expansion draft from the Oakland A's. His departure 
leaves only six of the 35 players selected by the Diamondbacks in 
the expansion draft still on the Arizona roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Frascatore, obtained by the Diamondbacks this spring in a trade  
with St. Louis, was 1-4 with a 4.09 ERA in 26 relief appearances 
for Arizona. He gave up a two-run homer in the ninth inning of the 
Diamondbacks' 12-2 victory over Anaheim on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks were willing to part with a young talent like  
Batista because of a dire need to shore up its shaky bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little bit of a risk, but sometimes you have to take a  
risk,'' Arizona manager Buck Showalter said in Anaheim, where the 
Diamondbacks were playing the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Plesac will join Greg Swindell as left-handers in the Arizona  
bullpen. The Diamondbacks, who lead the NL West, have blown 10 of 
21 save situations but there was no indication they look upon 
Plesac as a full-time closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said Fox, who played seven positions for Arizona last  
season, would be the regular shortstop, with Hanley Frias playing 
some at that position. Frias started at shortstop Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said the Diamondbacks do not want to move Bell back to  
shortstop because they believe Bell's shift is at least partly 
responsible for his strong season. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Womack, who played second base in Pittsburgh before being  
traded to Arizona this year, also is an option at shortstop, 
Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks believe their shortstop of the future is Danny  
Klassen, currently with Triple-A Tucson. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
