<DOCNO> APW19990612.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 10:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Patients Rights Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton renewed his push Saturday  
for Congress to pass legislation guaranteeing rights for medical 
patients, and said GOP proposals to reform managed care were ``a 
patients' bill of rights in name only.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used his first weekly radio address since the end of  
NATO bombing in Kosovo to highlight the safeguards he wants as part 
of a package of protections for the more than half of all Americans 
enrolled in managed-care plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must do more to make sure that when health care plans cut  
costs, they don't cut quality, and that the bottom line never 
becomes more important than patients' needs,'' the president said 
in remarks taped Friday for broadcast Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants legislation that would ensure patients have access  
to health care specialists and emergency room services, and protect 
them from switching doctors in the midst of treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The most controversial -- and most expensive -- provision that  
Democrats are pushing would give patients the right to sue health 
plans and collect damages when treatment is withheld. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have said the Democratic measures is too expensive  
and could lead employers to drop coverage. Senate Republicans have 
their own legislation on health maintenance organizations that 
would cost less but would cover fewer Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	While pleased by GOP support for the issue and a pledge by  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to bring managed-care 
legislation to a vote this summer, Clinton said the Republican 
proposals were inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republican leadership's legislation falls far short of  
providing American families the protection they need in a changing 
health care system,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton listed protections not in various GOP measures,  
including guaranteed access to specialists and recourse against 
health plans that provide poor-quality care. Republican HMO 
legislation also would exclude tens of millions of Americans from 
protections, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``A patients' bill of rights that doesn't provide these  
important protections is a patients' bill of rights in name only, 
and our people deserve better,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Clinton directed health plans used by federal  
employees and their families to implement the patients' bill of 
rights. And in April, he touted figures showing that this action is 
costing less than $10 per person per year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 03:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Fever Strikes Buffalo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Not since the Buffalo Bills earned their  
fourth consecutive Super Bowl trip in 1994 have fans in these parts 
been so pumped, looking again for that elusive major sports 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is that the Buffalo Sabres' opponent in the Stanley  
Cup finals is the Dallas Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas is the home of America's Team in football, the dreaded  
Cowboys who broke Buffalo's heart not once, but twice, with 
consecutive Super Bowl victories in 1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse yet, the Stars, the National Hockey League's best  
regular-season team, went into the finals heavily favored. The 
best-of-seven Stanley Cup finals are tied at one game each, with 
Game 3 to be played here tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	If a Buffalo team falls again to a Dallas team, Buffalo fan Bob  
Young said, ``I don't want to hear about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Stanley Cup win could boost the psyche of a city that's been  
dealt blow after blow from the outside world over its sports 
failures, harsh winters and economic hardships. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be worse. We could live in Buffalo,'' columnist Woody  
Paige wrote in The Denver Post after the Colorado Avalanche lost to 
the Stars. He said Buffalo would be worse ``for obvious reasons'' 
and because Buffalo has never won a Super Bowl, an NBA 
championship, a World Series or a Stanley Cup ``and likely won't 
again this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Buffalo falls more than Niagara,'' he declared.  
</P>
<P>
	Arun Jain, a marketing professor at the University at Buffalo,  
said an NHL championship would be good for the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Stanley Cup championship would give Buffalo a positive  
image; then, by inference, people would begin to think that there 
is something special about the city,'' Jain said. ``After they take 
a longer look at Buffalo, they'll learn that the city has a lot to 
offer beyond professional sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, it would make the city's long-suffering fans feel better.  
</P>
<P>
	``I am the consummate loser,'' said Dave Pietrowski, a Sabres  
and Bills season-ticket holder. ``I went to Syracuse University. 
I've been to two Final Fours, a Sugar Bowl, four Super Bowls, and 
my team has never won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Buffalo Bills quarterback Jim Kelly, who led his team to  
all those Super Bowls, is hoping the Sabres win. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are always ragging on the Bills and the people of  
Buffalo about those Super Bowls,'' he said. ``Maybe this will shut 
some people up.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brewers Retire Molitor's No. 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Paul Molitor, who spent the first 15 years of  
his career with Milwaukee, saw his No. 4 uniform retired by the 
Brewers on Friday night to fans' cheers of ``Paulie, Paulie, 
Paulie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only other Brewers to have their jerseys retired are Hank  
Aaron (44), Robin Yount (19) and Rollie Fingers (34). 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor was greeted with a long standing ovation and told the  
crowd that if elected to the Hall of Fame, ``I'll be proud to go in 
as a Brewer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been embraced by the fans here, and I want to thank you  
from the bottom of my heart for that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 21-year career, which ended last season, Molitor hit .306  
with 3,319 hits, eighth on the career list. He was a five-time 
All-Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor was with the Brewers from 1978-92. He is now a part-time  
broadcaster for the Minnesota Twins but said he would like to get 
more involved in ``terms of teaching or shaping'' young players for 
a team. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there was some ill feeling when he left the Brewers as  
a free agent in 1993, and again in 1996 when he chose to play for 
the Twins instead of returning to Milwaukee, Molitor said he could 
return to the Brewers one day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be foolish to close the doors on any avenues in this  
game,'' he said. ``I would say the door's open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor said many of his fondest memories are from his years as  
a Brewer, especially the friendships he made with Yount and Jim 
Gantner, both of whom spoke at the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I talk about a specific year, '82 is the one that sticks  
out, believe me,'' he said, referring to the year the Brewers won 
the AL pennant and lost a seven-game World Series to St. Louis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
