<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks Advance Without Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On Friday night, the big L stood for longshot,  
which was the only way to look at how the New York Knicks advanced 
into the NBA Finals after Larry Johnson went down with a knee 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Already undermanned with the loss of center Patrick Ewing, the  
Knicks shrugged off Johnson's second-period knee injury to overcome 
the Indiana Pacers 90-82 in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference 
Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, whose `Big L' arm sign has become his trademark after  
baskets, missed the celebration. He was in the hospital with 
strained right knee ligaments after Travis Best rolled into him 
midway through the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The collision left Johnson screaming in pain, clutching his knee  
and, some might have thought, taking the Knicks' chances down with 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't turn out that way.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, Larry's a great player and emotionally it takes a  
toll on your team,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Our guys 
fought. We had to just hang around. Somehow we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was the formula throughout the series and it worked again.  
At one point, Chris Childs made a third-quarter basket and formed 
the L with his arms, a reminder that the Knicks had Johnson on 
their mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Houston, who started the game missing four of five shots,  
hit 11 of his next 12 to lead all scorers with 32 points. Marcus 
Camby, who blossomed in the Indiana series, picked up much of 
Johnson's playing time and had 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to keep doing what I was doing after Larry went  
down,'' Houston said. ``I didn't want to put more pressure on 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Allan was huge,'' Van Gundy said. ``The will and the work and  
commitment they had, I feel good for those guys. It got to the 
point where all they cared about was winning. It's hard to get to 
but we got to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of Johnson seemed to be no big deal to the Knicks, who  
adjusted on the fly. Camby and Kurt Thomas picked up his playing 
time and, as they have throughout the playoffs, the Knicks found a 
way to win. 
</P>
<P>
	When Johnson went down, he remained on the floor for several  
minutes. He was immediately surrounded by teammates and helped off 
by Herb Williams and Chris Dudley, led into the locker room by Dr. 
Norman Scott, the team physician. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative and the preliminary diagnosis was sprained  
ligaments. Johnson was taken to a hospital for a precautionary MRI 
examination. He will be re-evaluated on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks' front line is already shorthanded after Ewing  
suffered a partial tear in his left Achilles, ending his season 
after two games of the Eastern Conference finals. Ewing led cheers 
from the bench as his team closed in on the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Practice should be interesting,'' Van Gundy said, thinking  
about the injuries. ``I'm going to get some (playing) time in 
practice. So that will be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was a vital cog in the Knicks' attack. His four-point  
play -- a 3-point field goal followed by a free throw -- with 5.7 
seconds left provided the deciding points in the Knicks' 92-91 
victory in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 5, Johnson hit consecutive 3-pointers down the stretch  
as New York pulled away for a 101-94 victory that put it in 
position to close out the Pacers at home. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was injured, Johnson had just scored two baskets after  
an 0-for-3 first quarter. He left the game having scored eight 
points in 14 minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks Advance Without Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On Friday night, the big L stood for longshot,  
which was the only way to look at how the New York Knicks advanced 
into the NBA Finals after Larry Johnson went down with a knee 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Already undermanned with the loss of center Patrick Ewing, the  
Knicks shrugged off Johnson's second-period knee injury to overcome 
the Indiana Pacers 90-82 in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference 
Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, whose `Big L' arm sign has become his trademark after  
baskets, missed the celebration. He was in the hospital with 
strained right knee ligaments after Travis Best rolled into him 
midway through the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The collision left Johnson screaming in pain, clutching his knee  
and, some might have thought, taking the Knicks' chances down with 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't turn out that way.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, Larry's a great player and emotionally it takes a  
toll on your team,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Our guys 
fought. We had to just hang around. Somehow we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was the formula throughout the series and it worked again.  
At one point, Chris Childs made a third-quarter basket and formed 
the L with his arms, a reminder that the Knicks had Johnson on 
their mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Houston, who started the game missing four of five shots,  
hit 11 of his next 12 to lead all scorers with 32 points. Marcus 
Camby, who blossomed in the Indiana series, picked up much of 
Johnson's playing time and had 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to keep doing what I was doing after Larry went  
down,'' Houston said. ``I didn't want to put more pressure on 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Allan was huge,'' Van Gundy said. ``The will and the work and  
commitment they had, I feel good for those guys. It got to the 
point where all they cared about was winning. It's hard to get to 
but we got to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of Johnson seemed to be no big deal to the Knicks, who  
adjusted on the fly. Camby and Kurt Thomas picked up his playing 
time and, as they have throughout the playoffs, the Knicks found a 
way to win. 
</P>
<P>
	When Johnson went down, he remained on the floor for several  
minutes. He was immediately surrounded by teammates and helped off 
by Herb Williams and Chris Dudley, led into the locker room by Dr. 
Norman Scott, the team physician. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative and the preliminary diagnosis was sprained  
ligaments. Johnson was taken to a hospital for a precautionary MRI 
examination. He will be re-evaluated on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks' front line is already shorthanded after Ewing  
suffered a partial tear in his left Achilles, ending his season 
after two games of the Eastern Conference finals. Ewing led cheers 
from the bench as his team closed in on the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Practice should be interesting,'' Van Gundy said, thinking  
about the injuries. ``I'm going to get some (playing) time in 
practice. So that will be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was a vital cog in the Knicks' attack. His four-point  
play -- a 3-point field goal followed by a free throw -- with 5.7 
seconds left provided the deciding points in the Knicks' 92-91 
victory in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 5, Johnson hit consecutive 3-pointers down the stretch  
as New York pulled away for a 101-94 victory that put it in 
position to close out the Pacers at home. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was injured, Johnson had just scored two baskets after  
an 0-for-3 first quarter. He left the game having scored eight 
points in 14 minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
