<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A bus collided head-on with a  
truck carrying apples in southwestern Brazil on Saturday, killing 
four people and injuring 20, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officer Ricardo Schneider in Cascavel, 600 miles southwest of  
Rio, said the bus was carrying mainly ``baggers,'' a local term for 
Brazilians who buy low-priced goods in nearby Paraguay and resell 
them illegally at home. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian aircraft manufacturer  
Embraer has won contracts worth $4.8 billion from European regional 
airlines, a record for the company, Brazilian media reported 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The orders are for 200 ERJ commuter jets, the Estado de Sao  
Paulo newspaper said. It did not name the buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The contracts were to be announced in Paris on Monday by Embraer  
President Mauricio Botelho, the daily reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Embraer is a former government-run company and chronic  
money-loser that turned around after it was privatized in 1994. 
Last year, it made a profit of $102.9 million, the first in its 
30-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Gunmen burst into a bar early Saturday  
and killed four women and three men in an apparent drug-related 
shooting, the Globo TV network reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Film footage showed cabinets and walls in the bar riddled with  
bullet holes. The Sao Paulo police department said it had no 
information on the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety-six people have died in 28 multiple-victim killings in  
Sao Paulo this year, Globo said. Most of the shootings are believed 
to have been carried out by drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Costa Rica's governing party on  
Saturday denied claims it received $1 million in campaign money 
from a Mexican policitian cited in a U.S. intelligence report as 
posing a ``significant criminal threat'' to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A government statement called ``slanderous'' accusations that  
Carlos Hank Gonzalez, a former Mexican Cabinet secretary, gave the 
money to the 1997 election campaign of President Miguel Angel 
Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carlos Hank didn't give a single cent to the Social Christian  
campaign, and that can be verified by anybody,'' the statement 
continued. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, three congressmen of the opposition National  
Liberation Party said they had information on the alleged campaign 
contributions. The opposition has called for a formal 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Media reports in May cited a U.S. intelligence report describing  
Hank Gonzalez and his sons as ``a significant criminal threat to 
the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Hank Gonzalez, one of the most prominent members  
of Mexico's ruling class, has denied the allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
