<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 09:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Soccer Team Expects Good Crowd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bruce Arena expects the U.S. men's soccer team  
to be at home in more than name only when it plays Argentina on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	When the national team played in the U.S. Cup in March, that  
wasn't the case. Throngs of fans cheered loudly for foreign players 
in the Americans' 3-1 victory over Guatemala in San Diego and their 
2-1 loss to Mexico in the championship game in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very much the visiting team,'' said Arena. ``I don't  
mind that -- it's a great challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Arena expects a pro-American crowd of 40,000 at RFK Stadium.  
Since an exhibition between Argentina and Mexico at Soldier Field 
in Chicago on June 9 drew a sellout crowd of 64,443, that makes 
Arena's prediction more than wishful thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time in a while,'' Arena said, ``I think we're  
going to see an American crowd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How the retooled U.S. squad will react against a world soccer  
power, and what strategy Argentina will employ, remain to be seen. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams last met in 1995, when the U.S. upset Argentina 3-0 in  
the Copa America Cup, but Argentina holds a lifetime 4-1 mark 
against the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	This match should be a gauge of Arena's impact since taking over  
as coach last year -- and of the Americans' progress since a dismal 
showing in World Cup 1998 that hastened Arena's arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	``The right way to find a balance is to be given great  
challenges,'' Arena said. ``We realize this is just a measuring 
stick of where we are as a team and where our players are as 
individuals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina is the third South American foe the U.S. has played  
this year. The Americans previously tied Bolivia 0-0 and beat Chile 
2-1. The Argentineans, who are favored to win this year's Copa 
America in Paraguay, will be a stern test. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Marcelo Bielsa's squad for Sunday's exhibition, however,  
does not include several standouts who were not invited, committed 
to other teams or declined to participate. 
</P>
<P>
	The most notable absence is injured striker Gabriel Batistuta,  
who leads the Italian league in scoring and netted nine goals in 
the past two World Cups. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to know what you're going up against,'' said U.S.  
midfielder Tony Sanneh, who has been playing with Hertha Berlin of 
the German League. ``But we have a general idea of what formations 
they're going to play. Hopefully we can make them adjust to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arena has summoned eight American players from foreign teams and  
10 more from Major League Soccer rosters. The U.S. will use the 
match as preparation for the FIFA Confederations Cup in Mexico in 
July. 
</P>
<P>
	Arena returns to the area where he led D.C. United to MLS titles  
in 1996 and 1997. While he continues to rebuild the U.S. team, 
Arena insists that his job description no longer includes selling 
American fans on the world's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not playing marketer,'' he said. ``I have enough problems  
trying to develop a team. .. The best way of marketing soccer is 
putting a good team on the field.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
