<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	US Accepts Russia's Kosovo Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States tried to put the best face  
on a dismaying hitch in plans for postwar Kosovo today, with 
predictions that NATO and Russian forces can work hand-in-hand to 
keep peace in the province. Russian troops beat NATO peacekeeping 
teams into Kosovo, stealing some thunder from the victorious 
alliance. The Russians, who arrived unannounced late yesterday, and 
the vanguard of a British force both occupied the key Pristina 
airfield. Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Henry Shelton said 
the two forces had a cordial meeting. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Tension Reported  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Streaming into Kosovo's capital,  
almost unopposed by retreating Serbs, NATO peacekeepers came 
face-to-face today with the Russian troops who beat them to the 
city. A U.S. official said the two sides were running ``a 
coordinated occupation,'' but some reports described tense moments 
between NATO troops and the small Russian force. U.S. and Russian 
negotiators are working to design a formal job for Russia in the 
Kosovo peacekeeping force. But there was no immediate result and no 
sign the column was planning to leave, as Russia's foreign minister 
had promised. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Killed in Michigan Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	BINGHAM FARMS, Mich. (AP) -- A psychiatrist who was gunned down  
by a man seeking treatment could have done little to help the 
severely disturbed patient, the doctor's family said today. Joseph 
Brooks Jr., 27, killed Dr. Reuven Bar-Levav and a woman and injured 
four others before killing himself at Bar-Levav's office yesterday 
afternoon. One of the wounded remained hospitalized in fair 
condition today. The gunman had been diagnosed elsewhere as a 
paranoid schizophrenic and had come to the office several times, 
said Dr. Leora Bar-Levav. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts See Computer Virus Trouble  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nervous calls to computer support lines dropped  
off sharply today after two frenzied days of combat against a 
software bug that attacks with the speed of the Melissa virus and 
the destructiveness of Chernobyl. Computer experts, however, feared 
that the spread of Worm.Explore.Zip will pick up again when 
employees return to work Monday, adding to the tens of thousands of 
machines infected with the file-eating bug. The virus, first 
detected June 6 in Israel, did most of its damage in the past two 
days, infecting computer systems at several big corporations. 

</P>
<P>
	S. Korea Heightens Attack Alert  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Communist North Korea sent patrol  
boats across a disputed sea border today after threatening to 
attack South Korean warships in contested waters of the Yellow Sea. 
The American-led U.N. Command, which oversees the fragile truce 
between the two bitter rivals, urged North Korea -- for a third time 
this week -- to hold a border military meeting to end the standoff. 
The armed standoff in the Cold War's last flashpoint entered its 
fifth day today, with the two Koreas hardening their stances after 
their ships nearly opened fire yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Former President Returns To Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the most vilified  
former Mexican president in recent memory, returned home today to 
the country he left in disgrace four years ago. The two-day trip 
was the first visit home for the man widely blamed for the crushing 
1995 peso crisis and recession. The tone of Salina's return stood 
in contrast to that of his triumphant departure from the presidency 
in December 1994, after six years of market-oriented reforms that 
his supporters said elevated Mexico out of the third world. 

</P>
<P>
	Health-Care Coverage Grows for Pets  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A growing number of people are paying up to  
$6,000 for kidney transplants and chemotherapy for their pets. 
``And why not?'' said Michael Garvey, who chairs the Animal Medical 
Center of New York's emergency department. ``After a long hard day 
at work, your pet is always happy to see you. You can't always say 
that about all the people in your home.'' Garvey is one of about 
2,600 animal doctors in Chicago for a weekend conference on pet 
treatments unheard of a few years ago and still largely unknown to 
many pet owners. 

</P>
<P>
	Dallas' Star Modano May Play  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dallas' high-scoring center Mike Modano,  
saying he is ``feeling a lot better'', is indicating he is ready to 
go in tonight's Stanley Cup finals game against the Buffalo Sabres. 
But Modano also said he would wait to see how he felt at game time 
before making his final decision. The series is tied 1-1. Modano, 
the Stars' regular-season leading scorer and all-around best 
player, hurt his left wrist when he was hit by Buffalo's Jay McKee 
in Game 2 on Thursday night. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
