<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gordon Takes Momentum Into Kmart 400 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- It has been a trying year for Jeff  
Gordon. The NASCAR poster boy, winner of three Winston Cup titles, 
is suddenly mortal. 
</P>
<P>
	For some reason his Chevrolet -- the familiar No. 24 car -- has  
more days when it runs like a lemon off the used-car lot. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Gordon appears to be the man to beat Sunday in the Kmart  
400 at Michigan Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon shattered his own track record with a qualifying lap at  
186.945 mph. That earned him the right to start on the pole, next 
to Ernie Irvan. Gordon, who has won the Cup points series three of 
the past four seasons, has finished sixth or better in his last 
eight races at this 2-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	And starting at the head of the pack frequently pays off at  
Michigan. In the 57 Winston Cup races held at the track since it 
opened in 1969, the winner has come from the first five rows 51 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	The pole winner has won 13 times.  
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to be able to run as fast as you can throughout the  
whole race,'' said Irvan, who won at Michigan in 1997. ``Obviously, 
when you're in the lead, you'll use a little more fuel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A fueling decision may have cost Gordon a chance to beat Bobby  
Labonte to the finish line last week at Dover, Del. But it has 
mainly been a balky car holding Gordon back. 
</P>
<P>
	His car did not finish four of the season's first 13 races. That  
equals Gordon's DNFs for the past two years combined. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely been a trying year for us, a little bit,''  
Gordon said. ``We've had lots of success the past few years, and 
when you've had that kind of success you want to live up to those 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's awesome pressure to live up to those expectations.''  
</P>
<P>
	Dale Jarrett, who leads the Winston Cup standings with 1,984  
points -- 51 more than Jeff Burton, knows exactly what Gordon is 
going through. Jarrett has chased Gordon the past three years, 
losing the Cup title by Gordon only 14 points in 1997 and finishing 
third last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trying to chase 'em down is always harder to me,'' Jarrett  
said. ``That's difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not impossible.  
</P>
<P>
	To equal last year's win total of 13, Gordon would have to win  
10 of the last 21 races in this 34-race season. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, after 13 races, Gordon ranked third in the standings.  
But he won 10 of the last 20 races. When the dust had settled, 
Gordon had 5,328 points and won the Cup series by 364 points over 
Mark Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	He is currently sixth in the standings, 339 points back.  
</P>
<P>
	``We look at where we're finishing,'' Gordon said. ``It says a  
lot for us to be sixth in the points and have that many DNFs. I 
think it just shows how well we are performing when we do finish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No kidding.  
</P>
<P>
	Gordon won the Daytona 500, won the Cracker Barrel 500 and won  
the California 500. Last week, he finished second at Dover and 
climbed from eighth to sixth in the standings. It was his seventh 
top-five finish this season, all of which have been third or 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's funny how last weekend at Dover like all of a sudden  
we're back on track,'' Gordon said. ``Everything is clicking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That might be bad news for the rest of the field.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
