<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Takes Comeback Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Four-time Olympic gold medalist Amy Van  
Dyken won a 50-meter freestyle race tonight, her first competitive 
race since she had shoulder surgery last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Dyken, 26, won gold medals in the 1996 Summer Games in the  
50 freestyle and 100 butterfly, and as a member of the 400 
freestyle and 400 medley relay teams. 
</P>
<P>
	But she injured her right shoulder while lifting weights on May  
10, 1997, and couldn't take a single stroke in the pool for months 
without significant pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Dyken, the American record-holder in the 50 at 24.87  
seconds, was timed in 25.95 Saturday night during the Charlotte 
UltraSwim. It wasn't close to her personal best, but it fulfilled 
her modest expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I wasn't going to have a good start because it hurts my  
shoulder a lot at the start,'' Van Dyken said. ``I usually build up 
(speed) during the race, and that's what I did. It looked like I 
was going to lose for a while, but I just kicked it into another 
gear, and it worked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Dyken, who has aspirations of competing in the 2000 Olympics  
in Sydney, Australia, is working her way back into shape. Charlotte 
was a positive step, one she hopes will help land her a spot on the 
U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, it's just make the team,'' Van Dyken said. ``I  
took that first step this morning in making my Olympic trials 
qualifying time, which I didn't have going into this meet. I've 
made the first step, the next step is to work hard, see what I can 
do and whatever happens is going to happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
