<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 06:44:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Begin Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India and Pakistan launched talks today  
aimed at resolving hostilities that have been raging for a month in 
the disputed mountain region of Kashmir, heightening tensions 
between the two nuclear powers. 
</P>
<P>
	With airstrikes and ground troops, India has been battling  
Islamic guerrillas who seized mountain positions in Kashmir in May. 
It accuses Pakistan of backing the guerrillas in a bid to alter the 
cease-fire line dividing the disputed territory between the two 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan has denied any ties to the guerrillas.  
</P>
<P>
	Before foreign ministers Jaswant Singh of India and Sartaj Aziz  
of Pakistan entered talks today in New Delhi, both sides continued 
to trade accusations over the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions flared in the capital during the talks as well. Riot  
police stopped protesters from marching on the Pakistani Embassy. 
They burned effigies of Aziz and the Pakistani prime minister, 
shouting, ``Sartaj Aziz go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said Friday that India's only objective was to persuade  
Pakistan to remove the forces and respect the Line of Control, as 
the 1972 cease-fire line is known. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kashmir, the Indian army continued shelling the seized  
mountain positions today. Officers in the state capital, Srinagar, 
said troops were engaged in close-quarters combat to recapture the 
icy mountains in the Batalik region of the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Delhi talks were clouded by Indian accusations that six  
soldiers were tortured in captivity in Pakistan and their bodies 
were mutilated. Pakistan's army, which handed the bodies to India 
on Thursday, denied the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	India also produced telephone transcripts between two top  
Pakistani generals it said support its claims the Pakistani 
military controls the guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	India says Pakistani troops are among the insurgents. Pakistan  
denies those claims and dismissed the phone transcripts as 
propaganda. 
</P>
<P>
	But Singh said the tapes raise ``serious doubts about  
(Pakistan's) professed aim of defusing tension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan says the guerrillas are from Islamic groups fighting  
for Kashmiri independence from majority Hindu India. Aziz said 
India was overreacting to the guerrillas' offensive and was 
escalating tensions along the border. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan have fought three wars, two of them over  
Kashmir, since they won independence from Britain in 1947. India 
controls two-thirds of the territory, and Pakistan has the 
remaining third. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim guerrillas have been leading an 11-year insurgency in  
Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 01:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shooting Outside Wal-Mart Kills Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A man critically wounded his ex-girlfriend  
and fatally shot her fiance outside the Wal-Mart store where both 
victims worked before killing himself, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting happened Friday afternoon in an employee parking  
lot near the store, but ``innocent shoppers were not targeted,'' 
police spokesman Dave Gouran said. 
</P>
<P>
	David M. Jones, 26, was killed and his fiancee, Robin Kerl, 24,  
was in critical condition at a Madison hospital with a gunshot 
wound to the neck. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman, Harvey Pierce, 45, was dead at the scene.  
</P>
<P>
	Jones and Kerl were engaged to be married. Pierce was Kerl's  
ex-boyfriend and had made past threats against the woman, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Store customers were told to stay inside after the shooting,  
said Molly Rogers, who was waiting to retrieve her van. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were in there maybe 10 minutes when we heard, `Attention  
Wal-Mart shoppers, due to uncontrollable circumstances do not leave 
the store,''' Rogers said. Customers ``weren't panicked about it, 
but everyone got real worried.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990612.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 18:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victory Gallop Wins Stephen Foster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer Elliott Walden wasn't sure how  
Victory Gallop would fare in his first start since a third-place 
finish in the Dubai World Cup in March. 
</P>
<P>
	His questions were answered quickly Saturday as the 4-year-old  
winner of the 1998 Belmont Stakes ran 1 1/8 miles in a track-record 
1:47.28 to win the $827,250 Stephen Foster Handicap for 3-year-olds 
and up at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This horse has been training just great,'' Walden said. ``I  
must have had 10 people come up to me the last two days and tell me 
I was a cinch just from seeing him train. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know about that Dubai thing. I've been waiting to  
run him and had been excited about it. Everybody wants to label the 
fact that they don't come back from Dubai well. I hope this puts it 
to bed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The advertised showdown between two former Triple Crown race  
winners eventually turned into a one-horse show. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Jerry Bailey and carrying 120 pounds, Victory Gallop --  
who finished second in the 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness to 
Real Quiet -- breezed past 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner 
Silver Charm in the stretch and beat him by 8 1/2 lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-year-old gray, ridden by 1999 Kentucky Derby and Preakness  
winner Chris Antley and carrying a race-high 123 pounds, broke 
strong but flattened out in the final furlong in losing his fourth 
consecutive race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just kind of ran an even race,'' said Antley, who was  
aboard the Bob Baffert-trained colt for the first time. ``I thought 
I had him in pretty good position but he just didn't fire when we 
needed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Victory Gallop, who earned $512,895, went off at 6-5 and paid  
$4.60, $2.60 and $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Nite Dreamer, who carried 110 pounds and was ridden by Pat Day,  
finished second, five lengths back, and paid $4.80 and $2.10. 
Littlebitlively, who carried 115 pounds and was ridden by Calvin 
Borel, was another three-quarters of a length back in third and 
paid $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Silver Charm were Precocity, Da Devil and Connecting  
Terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Littlebitlively, who lost by a head to Silver Charm in last  
year's Clark Handicap, dueled with Connecting Terms for the first 
three-quarters of a mile. As the field moved around the far turn, 
Nite Dreamer made his bid for the lead as Victory Gallop charged 
from the back of the seven-horse field to take the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said he was amazed by the power in Victory Gallop's  
stride as he took the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``He dropped back farther than I thought he would, about 12 or  
14 lengths off the lead,'' Bailey said. ``He was content to be 
there until I pulled the trigger. And then it was the most powerful 
rush I've felt around a turn since I've been riding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cigar made strong moves all the way in races, but when horses  
take off like that and make up the kind of time he did today, it's 
just devastating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ride was Antley's first major race since pulling up an  
injured Charismatic as the colt neared the finish line in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic broke two bones in his lower left foot and was  
retired following surgery to repair the damage. Veterinarians 
credited Antley, who jumped off and immediately picked the leg up 
to keep weight off it, with preventing more serious damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly feel revived because the horse is OK -- that was my  
biggest concern,'' Antley said. ``Charismatic has given me so much 
in my career and my comeback. ... He gave me some of my greatest 
moments ever. I felt something was wrong and what I did was simply 
instinct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Antley said Charismatic had been on his mind a lot since the  
Belmont but had no effect on the way he rode Silver Charm on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``New race, new horse, new beginning and a lot of hope,'' Antley  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
