<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Improvement Chain Files Ch. 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARGO, Md. (AP) -- Hechinger Co., the home improvement chain that  
has struggled against Home Depot and other rivals, has filed for 
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and said it will close 89 stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it will focus on 117 healthier stores in 21  
states. The reorganization plan announced Friday is subject to 
court approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The company reported a loss of $228 million in the last quarter.  
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1911, Hechinger grew into a Washington, D.C.,  
institution and one of the first large home-improvement chains in 
the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	By the early 1990s, however, it was clear that the Hechinger  
family had failed to recognize the threat posed by Home Depot and 
Lowe's, which were beginning to dot the suburbs with superstores. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger was sold two years ago for $507 million to Leonard  
Green &AMP; Partners, a Los Angeles investment group. Hechinger also 
combined Builders Square with two other chains to create the 
third-largest home-improvement chain. 
</P>
<P>
	But Home Depot and Lowe's have added stores and boosted profits,  
while Hechinger has struggled. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
