<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Birth Moms Fight for Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Jane's biggest fear is that the son she  
gave up for adoption almost 40 years ago will show up on her 
doorstep with a camcorder and questions she doesn't want to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	Who is my father?  
</P>
<P>
	Why did you give me away?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be very angry,'' she says. ``The idea of the adoption was  
to permanently sever the relationship with the child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jane, who asked that her real name not be used, is among  
opponents of Oregon's voter-passed Measure 58, which would allow 
adult adoptees to see sealed birth certificates. Birth mothers fear 
that if a court challenge by six anonymous birth mothers fails next 
month and the law goes into effect, the information will be used to 
find them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The birth mother is quarry to be hunted down,'' Jane says.  
``There's nothing there to protect them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the law say existing registries already list birth  
parents who want to be contacted, so last fall's vote threatens 
only those mothers, like Jane, who want their pasts left 
unexamined. 
</P>
<P>
	As a senior in college, Jane became pregnant to a man she'd been  
dating only briefly. It was the early 1960s and abortion was 
illegal, but Jane found two doctors known to perform them. Both 
refused because Jane had a tipped uterus, making the procedure too 
risky. 
</P>
<P>
	Four decades later, Jane has no wish to tell her child he was  
born because she couldn't find an abortionist. Neither does she 
want her son disrupting her life, demanding explanations and 
casting her in a role she never chose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel resentful that someone can come in and stake a  
claim on my life,'' she says. ``They want to sit down at the table 
and be a member of the family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case challenging open access to birth certificates is to be  
heard July 14 in Salem by Marion County Circuit Judge Albin 
Norblad. The six women who brought the suit claim they were 
promised confidentiality when they relinquished their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Their attorney, Frank Hunsaker, asserts Measure 58 violates a  
state constitutional provision against infringing on existing 
contracts because it wipes out promises of confidentiality made to 
birth mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Backers of the new law argue that no one had the authority to  
make such promises. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie, another birth mother who backs the plaintiffs, has -- at  
age 70 -- kept the story of her son's birth a secret for four 
decades. She sought an illegal abortion in the late 1950s but was 
told her pregnancy was too far along. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the years have gone on, it's kind of been like it was  
something that happened to someone else,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie's late husband already had children when they married, and  
she doesn't want her stepchildren to know she had a baby. But she 
also has concerns about the stranger who is her son -- her husband's 
investments left her comfortably provided for, and she worries her 
son might try to claim an inheritance or otherwise harm her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who knows what kind of person he is?'' she says. ``Who knows  
what he'd do?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the Measure 58 campaign, adoptees spoke out, often  
emotionally, about their searches for birth parents. Some who'd 
found their parents took reporters along to share the reunions. But 
the comparatively rare interviews with birth mothers paled in 
comparison because the women -- all anonymous -- so zealously guarded 
their privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie recognizes that insisting on anonymity hurt the birth  
mothers' ability to shape the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the news stories are slanted against the birth parents  
and for the adoptees,'' Marie says. ``I wish there was some way of 
letting people know it's not out of being coldhearted. I pray for 
him, but I don't want to meet him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jane frames the birth mothers' insistence on privacy as a  
feminist issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Her generation missed the freedom provided by the pill and the  
legalization of abortion. Adoption was the only workable choice in 
a culture that scorned unwed mothers. Maintaining privacy, Jane 
says, is the only way such women can define their own identities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boys and Girls Aid Society of Oregon, one of the state's  
largest adoption agencies, supports birth mothers who wish to 
remain anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	``Promises that have been made to them in the past must be  
addressed with respect and honor,'' the aid society said in a 
position paper issued during the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	But Madelyn Freundlich, executive director of the Evan B.  
Donaldson Adoption Institute in New York, says it's unlikely 
anonymity was promised to birth parents in most earlier adoptions. 
Decades ago, she explains, unwed mothers were often considered 
immoral and had no leverage to stipulate conditions for adoption. 
</P>
<P>
	Birth records were sealed to protect the adoptive families'  
privacy, she says, a practice that also concealed birth mothers' 
names. In various states, she says, plaintiffs challenging open 
adoption records have been unable to produce written promises. 
</P>
<P>
	``To the extent that any representation (about anonymity) was  
made, it was verbal,'' Freundlich says. 
</P>
<P>
	Freundlich says Oregon's unconditional access to birth records  
is an important test case. ``The eyes of many states are on 
Oregon,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindy lives in Oregon but would not be subject to the law  
because she surrendered her daughter for adoption in another state. 
But passage of Measure 58 turned her into an anonymous crusader for 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindy says her daughter was conceived in a ``terrifying, brutal  
stranger rape'' and that adoptees who want to use birth certificate 
information to contact unwilling parents are committing ``emotional 
rape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They are brutally invading our lives,'' she says. ``... I'm  
just as innocent as the adoptee. For most of us, this is the most 
painful thing we have ever been through.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
